{"term":"1957","caseName":"Federal Trade Commission v. National Casualty Company","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1957/435","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 09, 1958","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13359","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 435, Federal Trade Commission, Petitioner, versus National Casualty Company and Number 436, Federal Trade Commission versus the American Hospital and Life Insurance Company.","start":0,"stop":36.877,"duration":36.88},{"text":"Mr. Spritzer.","start":36.877,"stop":38.215,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":38.215,"stop":42.894,"duration":4.68},{"text":"These two consolidated cases come here on the Government's petitions from decisions of the Sixth and Fifth Circuits respectively.","start":42.894,"stop":56.404,"duration":13.51},{"text":"The question which they present is whether the Federal Trade Commission, in circumstances which I shall detail later, has been ousted by the McCarran-Ferguson Act of its jurisdiction to issue cease-and-desist orders directed against unfair and deceptive advertising by insurance companies.","start":56.404,"stop":90.216,"duration":33.81},{"text":"Before I sketch the essential fact of these two cases, I should like to take a very few minutes to state by way of introduction that the Federal Trade Commission has been engaged these past several years in a very active campaign to eliminate from the channels of interstate commerce, false and deceptive advertising by companies selling hospital health and accident insurance.","start":90.216,"stop":122.269,"duration":32.05},{"text":"There have been some 41 cases brought, many of them against major companies and there are various stages of development, the two here today being, of course, the first to reach this Court.","start":122.269,"stop":138.413,"duration":16.14},{"text":"They are important in the Commission's view, these two cases, not only because they will determine in very large measure the phase of the remaining cases, but also because the general situation which has given rise to all of these 41 proceedings is one which the Commission deems of both pressing and truly national concern.","start":138.413,"stop":165.599,"duration":27.19},{"text":"And that is so because health, hospital and accident insurance have grown so spectacularly in recent years.","start":165.599,"stop":173.304,"duration":7.71},{"text":"It appears, for example, that more than two thirds of all persons in the United States now carry some form of hospitalization insurance.","start":173.304,"stop":182.56,"duration":9.26},{"text":"And these forms of insurance are sold in very great part by companies which do business on a broad frequently national scale.","start":182.56,"stop":193.09,"duration":10.53},{"text":"Some of them selling on a strictly mail order basis, others by other techniques.","start":193.09,"stop":200.453,"duration":7.36},{"text":"Moreover, these companies more and more have come to employ techniques of mass advertising, in some cases, by television and radio or through national periodicals.","start":200.453,"stop":212.74,"duration":12.29},{"text":"And as I suppose everyone who has a mailing address is where many of them has employed the techniques which the advertising business refers to as saturation mail advertising.","start":212.74,"stop":227.082,"duration":14.34},{"text":"It was a consequence of the -- in consequence of this that Mr. Howrey, the then Chairman of the Federal Trade Commission in 1955, advised the House Committee on Interstate and Foreign Commerce, and I quote his words, “There has been more public interest in our investigation of this advertising than any investigation the Commission has undertaken in my memory.","start":227.082,"stop":255.799,"duration":28.72},{"text":"We got not hundreds, but thousands of letters of complaint and the public interest in response have been overwhelming.”","start":255.799,"stop":262.906,"duration":7.11}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you reading from your brief?","start":262.906,"stop":264.772,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I am reading from a House Report.","start":264.772,"stop":267.557,"duration":2.79},{"text":"It is not quoted in our brief, Your Honor -- Your Honor.","start":267.557,"stop":271.876,"duration":4.32},{"text":"And I might add that the Chairman of the Committee, before whom Mr. Howrey was appearing, then replied that it was the conviction of the Committee that there was a very great need for Federal Trade Commission action for the benefit of the companies insured.","start":271.876,"stop":291.769,"duration":19.89},{"text":"Now, with this background, I turn to the facts of these two particular cases.","start":291.769,"stop":299.621,"duration":7.85},{"text":"National, the respondent in 435, is incorporated and has its home office in Detroit, Michigan.","start":299.621,"stop":307.721,"duration":8.1},{"text":"It has 350 to 400 agents who are located in all 48 States in the District of Columbia and the territory of Hawaii.","start":307.721,"stop":318.828,"duration":11.11},{"text":"It's licensed to do business in all of those jurisdictions.","start":318.828,"stop":323.716,"duration":4.89},{"text":"It sent some brochures and advertising materials directly from Detroit to people throughout the country who maybe prospective buyers of insurance.","start":323.716,"stop":335.224,"duration":11.51},{"text":"However, the great mass of its material is apparently sent out in both ways to the agents and they, in turn, from such lists as they have or accumulated or accumulate, disseminate to the public.","start":335.224,"stop":352.335,"duration":17.11},{"text":"National's advertising materials challenged by the Federal Trade Commission complaint in this case had been in use for two years or more when the complaint was filed.","start":352.335,"stop":365.615,"duration":13.28},{"text":"The complaint charged and the Commission found that they were deceptive in some five major respects.","start":365.615,"stop":372.337,"duration":6.72},{"text":"I shall just quick and very briefly since, as I indicated in a moment, our issue here is jurisdictional rather than factual.","start":372.337,"stop":381.082,"duration":8.75},{"text":"The Commission charged and found that National's advertising first conveyed that the purchaser of the insurance could continue to renew this form of the insurance as he grew older and hence, obtained lifetime protection, whereas in fact, the policy has actually provided that they were cancellable at the option of the company.","start":381.082,"stop":404.731,"duration":23.65},{"text":"Two, the ads misrepresented the physical standards which the applicant for insurance had to meet.","start":404.731,"stop":411.565,"duration":6.83},{"text":"Three, they misrepresented that the insured receives broad and complete coverage in relation to hospitalization expenses and fixed -- sick benefits.","start":411.565,"stop":422.21,"duration":10.64},{"text":"There are being in fact numerous exceptions and qualifications in policies.","start":422.21,"stop":427.058,"duration":4.85},{"text":"Four, they misrepresented the amount of benefit payable in the event that the ensured had to go -- undergo surgery.","start":427.058,"stop":435.381,"duration":8.32},{"text":"Five, they misrepresented the duration of monthly sick benefits.","start":435.381,"stop":441.597,"duration":6.22},{"text":"American, the respondent in 436, is incorporated and has its home office in Texas, it does business selling health and accident insurance in 14 States where it -- it has applied since then, has agents.","start":441.597,"stop":459.126,"duration":17.53},{"text":"It sends its brochures and advertising materials similarly across state lines to its agents who in turn distribute to the public.","start":459.126,"stop":471.398,"duration":12.27},{"text":"I shan't detail the representations involved in the American case, suffice it that they also relate to the terms and conditions of the policy and to the coverage which they provided.","start":471.398,"stop":485.479,"duration":14.08},{"text":"The Commission in American's case found four out of five categories of violations charged has been proved.","start":485.479,"stop":495.284,"duration":9.81},{"text":"Now, as to the jurisdictional issue in these two cases, which is the only issue that the court below reached, let me note briefly one or two following additional facts.","start":495.284,"stop":509.186,"duration":13.9},{"text":"National alleged, and this is conceded, that the jurisdictions in which it does business with the exception of three States and the District Columbia have statutes, have state statutes under which the respective commissioners or departments of insurance might proceed, might issue cease-and-desist orders.","start":509.186,"stop":539.116,"duration":29.93},{"text":"There is no suggestion of a showing that any of these States have considered, ruled upon or proceeded in any way in relation to any of the practices.","start":539.116,"stop":551.758,"duration":12.64}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":551.758,"stop":552.956,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":552.956,"stop":553.892,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":553.892,"stop":564.472,"duration":10.58}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"They are what have been -- what has been called often times Little Federal Trade Commission Acts.","start":564.472,"stop":570.772,"duration":6.3},{"text":"And they authorized administrative agents, normally, the Commissioner of Insurance, to issue complaints, to conduct hearings and to enter cease-and-desist orders.","start":570.772,"stop":584.202,"duration":13.43},{"text":"They are patterned on the Federal Trade Commission Act.","start":584.202,"stop":587.84,"duration":3.64},{"text":"And 41 States, which have such statutes, are identical with one another and all of them speak of unfair practices and deceptive acts and practices in language virtually identical with the FTC Act.","start":587.84,"stop":605.267,"duration":17.43}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In -- in other -- in other words, you -- you -- if I understand you correctly, as to these States, if they chose to act, they could give identically the same relief that the Federal Trade Commission could give.","start":605.267,"stop":620.316,"duration":15.05}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Within -- within their state boarder.","start":620.316,"stop":622.562,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Within their state boarder --","start":622.562,"stop":623.229,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":623.229,"stop":623.536,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- yes, exactly.","start":623.536,"stop":625.243,"duration":1.71},{"text":"That's --","start":625.243,"stop":625.92,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":625.92,"stop":625.948,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that's the way I understood you.","start":625.948,"stop":626.395,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":626.395,"stop":627.134,"duration":0.74},{"text":"There's no question about that.","start":627.134,"stop":628.439,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Am I to --","start":628.439,"stop":628.497,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Both parties are in agreement as to that.","start":628.497,"stop":629.972,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- am I to infer therefore that you are not suggesting, or neither suggesting the topic.","start":629.972,"stop":637.458,"duration":7.49},{"text":"You're not suggesting that if you prevail that the Federal Trade Commission Acts apply, then, the respective state law is dealing the same subject matter and then go to sleep.","start":637.458,"stop":649.713,"duration":12.25}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, no.","start":649.713,"stop":650.44,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They're not --","start":650.44,"stop":650.578,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"The only question is --","start":650.578,"stop":650.945,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"There's no preemption (Voice Overlap) --","start":650.945,"stop":652.293,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":652.293,"stop":652.75,"duration":0.46},{"text":"The -- the only question here, sir --","start":652.75,"stop":653.509,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that they were both whether -- you also --","start":653.509,"stop":656.371,"duration":2.86}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct --","start":656.371,"stop":657.07,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":657.07,"stop":657.148,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Your Honor.","start":657.148,"stop":657.725,"duration":0.58},{"text":"The -- the States can certainly act in all events and the question is whether the federal arm is impotent in circumstances where the States have statutes but haven't undertaken any regulation in implementation of those statutes.","start":657.725,"stop":672.073,"duration":14.35}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":672.073,"stop":678.101,"duration":6.03}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think it's a matter of inference.","start":678.101,"stop":679.988,"duration":1.89},{"text":"I think we -- that's clear from the record.","start":679.988,"stop":682.341,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"You are seeking here to -- authority to release, for the Federal Trade Commission to release interstate channels or communication.","start":682.341,"stop":695.724,"duration":13.38},{"text":"Is that what it confirms?","start":695.724,"stop":696.341,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, and certainly there are no --","start":696.341,"stop":697.616,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"These are the mails from the agencies of commerce?","start":697.616,"stop":700.99,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it's not restricted to the mails.","start":700.99,"stop":704.251,"duration":3.26}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Other agencies of commerce was restricted to mails and -- and other agencies.","start":704.251,"stop":707.555,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let -- may I -- I'd better clarify our point.","start":707.555,"stop":710.816,"duration":3.26},{"text":"Interstate commerce is clearly involved because all of these advertising materials emanate from the home offices and then go to agents who in turn distributes.","start":710.816,"stop":719.816,"duration":9}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Are any of them radios, televisions?","start":719.816,"stop":721.66,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"No, not -- in these cases, we have the ads sent by mail or perhaps by railway express, the materials in any event across state lines to the agents who in turn distribute.","start":721.66,"stop":735.259,"duration":13.6},{"text":"In National, there may be some direct mailing from the home office, but we think that's -- that's immaterial for -- for our purposes.","start":735.259,"stop":742.423,"duration":7.16},{"text":"And our -- our basic position, which I shall be able to point out in a moment when I referred to the statutes is simply that so long as the State has not acted, there is no exclusion of the Federal Trade Commission's power, no divestiture of its power.","start":742.423,"stop":763.203,"duration":20.78}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"When you say the State does not acted, you may not mean have not acted statutorily, you mean have not proceeded.","start":763.203,"stop":770.21,"duration":7.01}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":770.21,"stop":771.066,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":771.066,"stop":771.166,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm using action in the sense of active regulation as distinguished from the mere enactment of a statute which in this case is really an enabling act.","start":771.166,"stop":782.712,"duration":11.55},{"text":"The statute -- none of the state statutes, like the Federal Trade Commission Act, none of them contained any sanctions.","start":782.712,"stop":790.135,"duration":7.42},{"text":"They just give the authority to regulate to a Commission.","start":790.135,"stop":793.583,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Just likely Federal Trade.","start":793.583,"stop":794.532,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":794.532,"stop":795.159,"duration":0.63},{"text":"And only if the administrative machinery is therefore brought into play and ultimately a cease-and-desist order issue is there any sanction because the cease-and-desist order, of course, operates only prospectively.","start":795.159,"stop":808.855,"duration":13.7}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Do any of these cases involved sending through the mail by the home office --","start":808.855,"stop":813.816,"duration":4.96}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":813.816,"stop":814.153,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to -- to householders, policyholders or just all through agents?","start":814.153,"stop":819.363,"duration":5.21}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"In the National case, approximately 5% of the ads are sent out from the home office in Detroit, the other 95% --","start":819.363,"stop":830.778,"duration":11.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":830.778,"stop":830.978,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"-- directly to prospective purchasers of insurance.","start":830.978,"stop":835.689,"duration":4.71},{"text":"The balance of the material is sent across state lines to the agents who -- who engage in distribution of the materials in their respective local area.","start":835.689,"stop":845.53,"duration":9.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"May -- may I ask one more explicit matter?","start":845.53,"stop":849.36,"duration":3.83},{"text":"Could any State, if or -- as a commissioner, if any State brought proceedings under Little Federal Trade Commission Act --","start":849.36,"stop":860.687,"duration":11.33}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":860.687,"stop":861.164,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- for the very abusive, which underlies the proceeding, if they have been met, if the state proceeding been met with the claim that it's -- that is interstate commerce and excluded from the state regulatory process?","start":861.164,"stop":879.361,"duration":18.2}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I can certainly conceive of cases in which that would be so.","start":879.361,"stop":883.341,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":883.341,"stop":883.461,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"For example, the mail order insurance company, it might be that many States would be helpless to reach the material coming into play.","start":883.461,"stop":891.326,"duration":7.87}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm not talking about practically, but could -- could the State proceedings be challenged on the ground that it's beyond the power of the State to see what the transaction was sought to be, let's say, for Houston because they involved interstate transactions.","start":891.326,"stop":909.902,"duration":18.58}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":909.902,"stop":910.99,"duration":1.09},{"text":"There is no question that the States on the facts of these cases --","start":910.99,"stop":914.823,"duration":3.83}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Could proceed --","start":914.823,"stop":915.55,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"-- could proceed and --","start":915.55,"stop":916.706,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- for this very case.","start":916.706,"stop":917.133,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"-- 48 States could enter 48 cease-and-desist orders against National.","start":917.133,"stop":922.862,"duration":5.73},{"text":"Our factual situation is that not one of the 48 has even considered proceedings.","start":922.862,"stop":927.311,"duration":4.45}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I just want (Inaudible)","start":927.311,"stop":928.766,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But your position also is even the 48 States Commission -- Commissioners did (Inaudible) nevertheless, there is a federal power that acts as the Commission did here.","start":928.766,"stop":939.75,"duration":10.98}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":939.75,"stop":940.309,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":940.309,"stop":940.359,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":940.359,"stop":940.619,"duration":0.26},{"text":"We would say that the States, under the McCarran-Ferguson Bill to which I will come, have top billing as it were.","start":940.619,"stop":949.877,"duration":9.26},{"text":"The State's systems are given the opportunity to act first.","start":949.877,"stop":955.995,"duration":6.12},{"text":"And if the States do act, we think that the federal power is pro tanto excluded, that is --","start":955.995,"stop":963.682,"duration":7.69}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now, if -- if the States do act, you mean not act in the sense as I understand you to say all the plea have acted, that is by adopting statutes?","start":963.682,"stop":973.102,"duration":9.42},{"text":"They must in fact attempt to reach the particular case and if -- if that's done, that would be a defense to win the effort on the part of Federal Trade Commission Act.","start":973.102,"stop":982.782,"duration":9.68}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":982.782,"stop":982.8,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Even by that 48 States or what?","start":982.8,"stop":985.832,"duration":3.03},{"text":"You -- you said pro tanto.","start":985.832,"stop":987.906,"duration":2.07},{"text":"Suppose in X number of States, proceedings are actually begun like unto the immediate proceedings before us, and then suppose X number is three or five or 27 or 48, now, what is the effect of that from this procedure?","start":987.906,"stop":1007.146,"duration":19.24}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"McCarran-Ferguson Act, I think, has as its policy that each State may regulate for itself for the protection of its own citizens.","start":1007.146,"stop":1017.023,"duration":9.88},{"text":"And if it does, that is all the regulation that there is to be.","start":1017.023,"stop":1022.051,"duration":5.03},{"text":"There is not to be double regulation --","start":1022.051,"stop":1025.123,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean --","start":1025.123,"stop":1025.161,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"-- so that any if State acts, then the Federal Trade Commission, I would say, cannot enter an order which would deal with the practices of an insurer within the borders of that State.","start":1025.161,"stop":1039.618,"duration":14.46},{"text":"If New Jersey has a proceeding and says that National can't distribute this advertising literature in New Jersey and then the Federal Trade Commission comes in and files a complaint, I would say that the Federal Trade Commission's order could only be made effective in relation to the other 47 States.","start":1039.618,"stop":1059.99,"duration":20.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, suppose that this -- this (Inaudible) meeting, if isn't summed up, of the House of Governors, there's an agreement among the 48 Governors that they will instruct their power to the Attorney General to begin those proceedings and 48 proceedings start or initiated in the 48 States --","start":1059.99,"stop":1077.576,"duration":17.59}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1077.576,"stop":1078.175,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that displaces all the Federal Trade Commission?","start":1078.175,"stop":1082.403,"duration":4.23}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, certainly if the Federal Trade Commission has not at that point proceeded, it would not proceed and --","start":1082.403,"stop":1088.01,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I'm not asking about policy, I'm asking about the limitation of power.","start":1088.01,"stop":1092.898,"duration":4.89}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think perhaps regulation would begin with the institution of a specific complaint.","start":1092.898,"stop":1100.712,"duration":7.81},{"text":"But certainly, I would say, it does not begin with the mere enactment of an enabling statute giving legislative --","start":1100.712,"stop":1109.176,"duration":8.46}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that.","start":1109.176,"stop":1109.433,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"-- power to the administrator and that's our case.","start":1109.433,"stop":1110.671,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You've made that -- you've made that clear --","start":1110.671,"stop":1112.527,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1112.527,"stop":1112.567,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but I'm not wholly clearer to the effects of the actual beginning of the process of enforcing state laws.","start":1112.567,"stop":1121.87,"duration":9.3},{"text":"And I gather from what you last said, if assuming there is no sham about it, 48 States get going.","start":1121.87,"stop":1128.34,"duration":6.47},{"text":"That's the plan of the Federal Trade Commission, is that right?","start":1128.34,"stop":1130.953,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"I would think so.","start":1130.953,"stop":1131.54,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's your position.","start":1131.54,"stop":1132.157,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"I would think so.","start":1132.157,"stop":1132.953,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"But also -- suppose you -- they never could get going on -- on this 5% or 6% of -- part of -- the -- the out-of-state home office in using the mails to bring stuff in.","start":1132.953,"stop":1145.096,"duration":12.14}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, maybe one would have a substantive due process question there.","start":1145.096,"stop":1151.113,"duration":6.02},{"text":"We, of course, do not concede that anything that State cannot regulate is in the federal regulation.","start":1151.113,"stop":1160.821,"duration":9.71}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"How -- how that home office would be reached as a practical matter.","start":1160.821,"stop":1164.344,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1164.344,"stop":1164.883,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1164.883,"stop":1165.961,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- in our cases here now, 100% of the material in the American case and 95% in the National case is distributed by the local agents after they get it from the home office and certainly as to those portions, the -- we have no doubt that the States could, if they chose, effectively regulate.","start":1165.961,"stop":1187.827,"duration":21.87}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) State of the home office regulating in the way would bar the use of the mail (Inaudible)","start":1187.827,"stop":1202.694,"duration":14.87}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I have relation to regulation by each of the States in which the material was disseminated.","start":1202.694,"stop":1209.177,"duration":6.48},{"text":"I think certainly each State has the power and the legitimate interest to prevent dissemination within the State of false and deceptive material.","start":1209.177,"stop":1220.72,"duration":11.54}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) sending it through the agents by mail in each of the other 47 States?","start":1220.72,"stop":1229.749,"duration":9.03}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, perhaps the home offices -- perhaps the -- the only State conceivably would be the State of the corporation.","start":1229.749,"stop":1234.854,"duration":5.11}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- that was my question, whether the State of the home office could, under some statute, forbids the home office from mailing this material.","start":1234.854,"stop":1247.321,"duration":12.47},{"text":"Of course, they might.","start":1247.321,"stop":1248.051,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"I think perhaps they might.","start":1248.051,"stop":1248.739,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They might again.","start":1248.739,"stop":1250.208,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"The answer is it might.","start":1250.208,"stop":1251.166,"duration":0.96},{"text":"I think most of the state statutes in terms would not permit that because most of the state statutes deal with misrepresentations occurring within the State and I take it that this representation to the public occurs at the place of dissemination rather than at the place where the home office is sending material out to its own agents.","start":1251.166,"stop":1277.129,"duration":25.96},{"text":"So -- yes.","start":1277.129,"stop":1278.686,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1278.686,"stop":1286.264,"duration":7.58}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"It does.","start":1286.264,"stop":1286.944,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1286.944,"stop":1289.371,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"It does and I -- I wish to get to it immediately.","start":1289.371,"stop":1292.687,"duration":3.32}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"May I interrupt with just one more question, Mr. Spritzer?","start":1292.687,"stop":1294.534,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1294.534,"stop":1297.611,"duration":3.08}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"At the outset, you -- you enumerated five different types of misrepresentation.","start":1297.611,"stop":1306.372,"duration":8.76},{"text":"I think it was in the case of National.","start":1306.372,"stop":1308.379,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1308.379,"stop":1309.657,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, let us suppose that State A selects one of those types of misrepresentation and proceeds against National for that one and only that one type of misrepresentation, what is the position of the Federal Government then as to the others?","start":1309.657,"stop":1334.06,"duration":24.4},{"text":"Could it -- could it then proceed against the company on the others?","start":1334.06,"stop":1339.793,"duration":5.73}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that if the state officer, let us say the Commissioner of Insurance made a determination or a ruling, be it formal or informal, that -- that only certain of these representations were serious not in his view that he was going to proceed against it or if he determines that some were permissible and others might not be, I don't think that we could then regulate.","start":1339.793,"stop":1368.024,"duration":28.23},{"text":"I think his determination would be dispositive as to the protection of the citizens of that State are going to get.","start":1368.024,"stop":1380.011,"duration":11.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, you think the State, if the Federal Trade Commission took affirmative action and the State of New York, for example, said, “Well, we don't agree and we will -- we want this advertising in New York,” that they could overrule the Federal Trade Commission.","start":1380.011,"stop":1396.554,"duration":16.54}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"I would not concede that was so.","start":1396.554,"stop":1399.132,"duration":2.58},{"text":"If the Federal Trade Commission already had an outstanding order because I would think that once jurisdiction attached to issue the Federal Trade Commission order that it would not thereafter be absolute.","start":1399.132,"stop":1413.256,"duration":14.12},{"text":"If, on the other hand, New York had determined before there was any outstanding federal injunction for itself, which representations were good and which were bad, then I would say that that was the end of the matter so far as the federal --","start":1413.256,"stop":1428.382,"duration":15.13}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean if the Federal Trade Commission stepped in at this stage of the matter and started complaints against -- in every State involving companies selling in all States of the union that would -- that would preempt the matter from the States, any of those States, do you think?","start":1428.382,"stop":1446.979,"duration":18.6}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"The States could always proceed for themselves but I don't -- what -- my suggestion was that the federal cease-and-desist order, if it had been entered before there were any state proceeding, would not be vacated merely because the State thereafter brought a proceeding.","start":1446.979,"stop":1464.599,"duration":17.62},{"text":"Now, the State could still go in its own proceeding.","start":1464.599,"stop":1467.359,"duration":2.76},{"text":"Let me illustrate.Suppose the Federal Trade Commission finds that the representations are not deceptive, all of the 48 States could each consider for itself, each for itself, whether it wanted to prohibit some of the representation or if the Federal Trade Commission concludes that the advertising is defective.","start":1467.359,"stop":1491.183,"duration":23.82},{"text":"It might well be that the State Commissioners of the insurance would still want to obtain a state cease-and-desist order against the same practices, so they could police it and go into the state court.","start":1491.183,"stop":1504.059,"duration":12.88},{"text":"Our question here is not whether the States may act, but they can in all events.","start":1504.059,"stop":1509.858,"duration":5.8},{"text":"The question is when the Federal Government is disabled from acting.","start":1509.858,"stop":1514.982,"duration":5.12},{"text":"Now, I -- I think it is the statutory question basically.","start":1514.982,"stop":1520.476,"duration":5.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So you also state the States have (Inaudible)","start":1520.476,"stop":1524.381,"duration":3.9}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1524.381,"stop":1525.55,"duration":1.17},{"text":"And even if they are later, they can supplement.","start":1525.55,"stop":1530.204,"duration":4.65},{"text":"They can also come in and have their own orders and make their own determination.","start":1530.204,"stop":1535.788,"duration":5.58},{"text":"Now, I need hardly spend any time on the Federal Trade Commission Act, instead it's so familiar to the Court.","start":1535.788,"stop":1542.266,"duration":6.48},{"text":"We have set it forth on page 3.","start":1542.266,"stop":1545.423,"duration":3.16},{"text":"I do point out that it is with the Federal Trade Commission Act that we begin and not with McCarran-Ferguson because the FTC Act is the organic act which confers upon it, upon the Commission its jurisdiction.","start":1545.423,"stop":1559.645,"duration":14.22},{"text":"And the courts below, I think, erroneously proceeded from the premise that they were to look in McCarran-Ferguson to find commission jurisdiction.","start":1559.645,"stop":1570.033,"duration":10.39},{"text":"Section 5, which relates to unfair and deceptive acts and practices, is set out in full at page 3.","start":1570.033,"stop":1577.31,"duration":7.28},{"text":"Let me note only in passing that the FTC Act made no exception for the business of insurance, though it did for some other businesses like banking and common carriage.","start":1577.31,"stop":1587.202,"duration":9.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's a little retrospective interpretation.","start":1587.202,"stop":1590.478,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1590.478,"stop":1594.443,"duration":3.96},{"text":"The McCarran-Ferguson Act is set forth in our brief at pages 4 and 5.","start":1594.443,"stop":1602.191,"duration":7.75},{"text":"The statement of purpose at the outset, at the top of page 4, is that continued regulation and taxation by the several States of the business of insurance is in the public interest.","start":1602.191,"stop":1615.817,"duration":13.63},{"text":"And then it goes on to say that silence on the part of Congress shall not impose any barrier to the regulation or taxation by the State.","start":1615.817,"stop":1626.137,"duration":10.32},{"text":"Then, in Section 2, consistently with that general declaration of purpose, we find that 2 (a) provides that the business of insurance shall be subject to the laws of the several States, which relate to the regulation or taxation of such business.","start":1626.137,"stop":1643.687,"duration":17.55},{"text":"And (b) goes on to say that no Act of Congress shall be construed to invalidate, impair or supersede any law enacted by any State for the purpose of regulating the business of insurance.","start":1643.687,"stop":1659.817,"duration":16.13},{"text":"And then, we come to the proviso clause which is the crucial sentence for these cases, \"Provided that after June 30, 1948, the Sherman Act, the Clayton Act and the Federal Trade Commission Act shall be applicable to the business of insurance to the extent that such business is not regulated by state laws.","start":1659.817,"stop":1688.949,"duration":29.13},{"text":"Now, narrowly, I think our question here is what do the four words regulated by state law mean as used in the statute?","start":1688.949,"stop":1700.337,"duration":11.39}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, whether the mere enacting of state statutes in this subject is regulation or not, is that it?","start":1700.337,"stop":1705.701,"duration":5.36}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, Your Honor.","start":1705.701,"stop":1706.76,"duration":1.06},{"text":"And that position, that the mere enactment of state enabling statutes, which set out general standards, impose no sanctions, delegate all authority to regulate to an administrative agency.","start":1706.76,"stop":1723.208,"duration":16.45},{"text":"That the mere enactment of such statute is not -- isn't position that respondents take which leads them in this case to argue that even though there has been no regulation in fact, no consideration by the States of the practices which are challenged in these cases.","start":1723.208,"stop":1742.687,"duration":19.48},{"text":"Even so, they would say in their sentence, there has been regulation because there is a law on the books under which the Commissioner of Insurance, if he knew about this or learned about it and if he chose to proceed and to conduct a hearing, could or might enter at all.","start":1742.687,"stop":1764.39,"duration":21.7}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now, Mr. Spritzer, in the National case, I notice that this order is directed to distribution in Mississippi, Rhode Island, Montana, Missouri or the District of Columbia.","start":1764.39,"stop":1774.84,"duration":10.45},{"text":"Now, didn't you say to us earlier that at least in the District of Columbia, there's no such regulatory statute?","start":1774.84,"stop":1780.353,"duration":5.51}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"There are several States in which there is no statute.","start":1780.353,"stop":1784.142,"duration":3.79},{"text":"I've been addressing myself to the situation which takes in more than 40 of the States where there is a statute.","start":1784.142,"stop":1792.066,"duration":7.92}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't that the National case?","start":1792.066,"stop":1793.834,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, National does business in 48 States.","start":1793.834,"stop":1796.212,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm looking -- am I looking at the wrong order at page 202 --","start":1796.212,"stop":1799.827,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"You're looking --","start":1799.827,"stop":1799.987,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of the record.","start":1799.987,"stop":1800.026,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"-- at the National record at 202?","start":1800.026,"stop":1802.123,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1802.123,"stop":1808.446,"duration":6.32},{"text":"I don't know.","start":1808.446,"stop":1808.795,"duration":0.35},{"text":"I'm -- I am looking at an order where it seems to be limited in its application with the State by name.","start":1808.795,"stop":1815.847,"duration":7.05}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"You're looking at the Examiner's decision, Your Honor.","start":1815.847,"stop":1818.643,"duration":2.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, was that it?","start":1818.643,"stop":1819.361,"duration":0.72},{"text":"I see.","start":1819.361,"stop":1820.71,"duration":1.35},{"text":"All right.","start":1820.71,"stop":1821.418,"duration":0.71},{"text":"Don't let me waste your time.","start":1821.418,"stop":1822.426,"duration":1.01},{"text":"Go ahead.","start":1822.426,"stop":1825.522,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"As I was saying I -- I think our -- our question is, what regulation by a state law means as used in this Act?","start":1825.522,"stop":1835.271,"duration":9.75},{"text":"Now, one will note that the sentence immediately precedingly proviso speaks about any law enacted by any State.","start":1835.271,"stop":1849.365,"duration":14.09},{"text":"However, the proviso declares that there shall be federal jurisdiction to the extent that such business is not regulated by state laws.","start":1849.365,"stop":1860.204,"duration":10.84},{"text":"Now, I -- I suggest that if Congress had proposed to do so, it would have been a very easy matter to make the incidence of federal power depend upon the enactment of state law.","start":1860.204,"stop":1877.052,"duration":16.85},{"text":"Indeed, in the very paragraph, we're here concerned with.","start":1877.052,"stop":1880.622,"duration":3.57},{"text":"Congress speaks of an act -- enactments under state law.","start":1880.622,"stop":1885.567,"duration":4.94},{"text":"Yet, the statute does not provide that the existence of state legislation or the enactment of state law will automatically exclude the Federal Trade Commission from regulating interstate transactions terminating in that State.","start":1885.567,"stop":1906.666,"duration":21.1},{"text":"On the contrary, the exception is phrased in terms of regulation and we say that regulation and legislation are not unanimous.","start":1906.666,"stop":1921.685,"duration":15.02},{"text":"It is also relevant I think that many federal Acts and many assertions of federal power are made by Congress to depend specifically on whether there is a state law.","start":1921.685,"stop":1935.596,"duration":13.91},{"text":"Here, we have a -- a different choice of language, not the word \"legislation\" or not enactment of state laws, but the use of the word \"regulation\".","start":1935.596,"stop":1949.884,"duration":14.29},{"text":"Now, I don't suggest that one should consider this simply as a -- as a dictionary proposition, certainly it is important to look at the purposes and such light -- to consider such light as maybe cast catch by the history of McCarran-Ferguson.","start":1949.884,"stop":1976.361,"duration":26.48},{"text":"Now, as the Court is -- I'm sure aware, McCarran-Ferguson was a direct response by the Congress to the decision of this Court in 1944 in United States against South-Eastern Underwriters.","start":1976.361,"stop":1994.829,"duration":18.47},{"text":"That decision in a Sherman Act case determined for the first time for overruling precedents going back for so many years that the business of insurance was commerce in the sense of the Commerce Clause.","start":1994.829,"stop":2017.68,"duration":22.85},{"text":"Consequently, the Court reinstated a Sherman Act indictment against a group of insurance underwriters.","start":2017.68,"stop":2026.943,"duration":9.26},{"text":"Immediately, following that opinion, the States and the insurance companies made very strong representations to the Congress, asserting that if the Commerce Clause restrictions apply to the States, to their regulatory measures and to their taxing statutes, that many of the existing state systems, established state systems with the effect it was claimed that there was great confusion and doubt, and that it couldn't be set what state laws would be held to be burdened upon commerce or to be discriminatory against commerce and -- and what -- what is not.","start":2026.943,"stop":2076.697,"duration":49.75},{"text":"Now, it was against this background that Congress passed McCarran-Ferguson.","start":2076.697,"stop":2083.181,"duration":6.48},{"text":"There's no question that Congress meant to permit the state systems to operate as they had prior to the South-Eastern Underwriters decision.","start":2083.181,"stop":2100.308,"duration":17.13},{"text":"We don't, for a moment, challenge that.","start":2100.308,"stop":2104.523,"duration":4.22},{"text":"What we do say is that McCarran-Ferguson did not intend to leave any no man's land, any vacuum in which there would be no regulation.","start":2104.523,"stop":2122.35,"duration":17.83},{"text":"It wanted to provide for situations in which the States could not act, perhaps for constitutional reasons that applied to particular facts.","start":2122.35,"stop":2132.602,"duration":10.25},{"text":"And it wanted to provide for regulation, we believe, in situations in which the States, though they might act did not choose to act or fail to act.","start":2132.602,"stop":2149.562,"duration":16.96},{"text":"I would like to turn for a few minutes to such history as we have which bears on the meaning of this proviso clause.","start":2149.562,"stop":2167.742,"duration":18.18},{"text":"There were separate bills introduced in each of the two Houses in 1945, following the South-Eastern Underwriters case.","start":2167.742,"stop":2178.821,"duration":11.08},{"text":"The bills in each House would have provided in one way or another that the States would continue to regulate what they had in the past, the insurance business.","start":2178.821,"stop":2192.927,"duration":14.11},{"text":"The House Report and also Senator McCarran on the floor of the Senate both pointed out that there were limitations upon what the States could do in relation to out-of-state companies, due process limitations.","start":2192.927,"stop":2213.692,"duration":20.76},{"text":"And both the Senate and the House Reports go on to state that the respective bills are designed to ensure adequate and effective regulation.","start":2213.692,"stop":2229.265,"duration":15.57},{"text":"Now, McCarran-Ferguson states to be sure that the Federal Government shall not impair the state systems.And the proviso clause declares to be sure that if the States act, the Federal Government will not act.","start":2229.265,"stop":2245.93,"duration":16.66},{"text":"We suggest that it is one thing to say that the Federal Government shall not impose either conflicting or double regulation.","start":2245.93,"stop":2257.314,"duration":11.38},{"text":"It is quite another thing to say that the Federal Government is precluded from acting where the States are not providing any regulation.","start":2257.314,"stop":2267.942,"duration":10.63},{"text":"Now, what light is --","start":2267.942,"stop":2268.9,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Now -- now, if I might interrupt.","start":2268.9,"stop":2271.088,"duration":2.19},{"text":"You used the word (Inaudible), is that my understanding?","start":2271.088,"stop":2275.353,"duration":4.26},{"text":"You used the word several times “regulation” which, to my mind, is a vastly different thing than the phrase “regulated by state law”, is it not?","start":2275.353,"stop":2284.955,"duration":9.6}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think all state regulation would have to be by or pursuant to state law.","start":2284.955,"stop":2290.359,"duration":5.4},{"text":"But what I'm trying to distinguish between is a piece of legislation which delegates authority to an administrative agency.","start":2290.359,"stop":2306.68,"duration":16.32},{"text":"The legislation itself and the regulation, which I think is only completed under a statute of this kind when the administrative machinery is used.","start":2306.68,"stop":2318.784,"duration":12.1},{"text":"What I have in mind, I think, is what was very colorfully stated by the late Justice Jackson in the Ruberoid case.","start":2318.784,"stop":2331.207,"duration":12.42},{"text":"There, he was not talking about the Federal Trade Commission Act but about the Robinson-Patman Act.","start":2331.207,"stop":2339.104,"duration":7.9},{"text":"And in speaking of Robinson-Patman, he considered the administrative process.","start":2339.104,"stop":2345.326,"duration":6.22},{"text":"He first pointed out that Robinson-Patman sets up general standards.","start":2345.326,"stop":2350.849,"duration":5.52},{"text":"And then, he went on to say, “Such legislation,” I'm looking at page 53 of the Government's brief, “represents in inchoate law, in the sense that it does not lay down rules which call for immediate compliance on paying of punishment by judicial process.","start":2350.849,"stop":2370.572,"duration":19.72},{"text":"The intervention of another authority must mature and perfect an effective rule of conduct before one is subject to coercion.”","start":2370.572,"stop":2380.24,"duration":9.67},{"text":"And then, he goes on to develop the -- the points that under a statute like this, there is an expanded legislative power which goes to the administrative agency.\"","start":2380.24,"stop":2394.005,"duration":13.77},{"text":"And only when the general standards of the statute are given meaning and content in the specific case, only when a rule or order is issued,” he says, “does one have regulation,\" and that is the argument we are making here.","start":2394.005,"stop":2413.991,"duration":19.99},{"text":"And we think that that is the sense in which one should read regulated by state law in this statute.","start":2413.991,"stop":2422.021,"duration":8.03},{"text":"If one is to avoid the situation where there will be a regulatory void, the experience has been, as perhaps might have been anticipated, perhaps because of the difficulties of the States in dealing with this situation, the experience in any event has been that the States has not been acting in this field.","start":2422.021,"stop":2447.508,"duration":25.49},{"text":"Now, we think that McCarran-Ferguson made clear that the States could act.","start":2447.508,"stop":2454.09,"duration":6.58},{"text":"It made clear moreover that they might act if they chose free of Commerce Clause restrictions.","start":2454.09,"stop":2460.492,"duration":6.4},{"text":"But we don't think that federal regulation in the sense that I'm speaking about, regulation by the institution of administrative proceedings and the issuance of administrative orders that such federal regulation is precluded unless there is at least some consideration, some ruling, some determination by the State.","start":2460.492,"stop":2485.062,"duration":24.57},{"text":"Now, I don't say that the State has to decide that it will file a cease-and-desist proceeding.","start":2485.062,"stop":2491.251,"duration":6.19},{"text":"I think the State might rule through its Commissioner or other officer that certain practices from the standpoint of that State are all right.","start":2491.251,"stop":2502.316,"duration":11.06},{"text":"And if it does that, we concede that that is a ruling or determination, that is regulation which would prevent a federal order from being applied to the insurance company doing business in that State.","start":2502.316,"stop":2518.718,"duration":16.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But there must be some avow -- some formal manifestations, some pronouncement that will advise the Federal Trade Commission which the Insurance Commission of Idaho or Georgia or Wyoming or mainly on the job.","start":2518.718,"stop":2532.687,"duration":13.97},{"text":"Is that right?","start":2532.687,"stop":2533.545,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't say there has to be a formal order.","start":2533.545,"stop":2535.843,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, how would he know if it was not a formal?","start":2535.843,"stop":2537.73,"duration":1.89},{"text":"There must be some public evidence (Voice Overlap) --","start":2537.73,"stop":2540.857,"duration":3.13}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Some -- something --","start":2540.857,"stop":2541.665,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The Insurance Commissioner of Wyoming had made around the job, is that right?","start":2541.665,"stop":2545.801,"duration":4.14}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that they had made a ruling.","start":2545.801,"stop":2547.899,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but --","start":2547.899,"stop":2548.547,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"So, if it's -- yes.","start":2548.547,"stop":2549.946,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It can't be that he -- that he is a (Inaudible) man and has worried about it, studied it and decided that there's nothing to proceed again.","start":2549.946,"stop":2560.071,"duration":10.13},{"text":"That will do.","start":2560.071,"stop":2561.58,"duration":1.51},{"text":"He must make that manifest, somehow or rather that the reaches the Federal Trade Commission unconstitutionality.","start":2561.58,"stop":2566.554,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, the -- if the Federal Trade Commission institutes a proceeding against National as it did here and National can come in and show any ruling or can produce an affidavit, the State has acted in the matter.","start":2566.554,"stop":2580.407,"duration":13.85},{"text":"I think that's perfectly sufficient to establish an affirmative defense that the Federal Trade Commission has no jurisdiction in relation to that State.","start":2580.407,"stop":2587.655,"duration":7.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that -- is that what the judge (Inaudible)","start":2587.655,"stop":2592.38,"duration":4.72},{"text":"Could -- could you say that likely without having litigation, whether he did or didn't act, whether he did or didn't consider, whether he has sufficiently considered (Inaudible) from litigation?","start":2592.38,"stop":2603.579,"duration":11.2}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"I-- I -- I'm --","start":2603.579,"stop":2604.616,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":2604.616,"stop":2604.936,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"-- not suggesting to the Court that either the Federal Trade Commission, Your Honor, or the federal courts are to make at any stage a qualitative judgment as to whether the State Commissioners are doing a good job.","start":2604.936,"stop":2619.68,"duration":14.74},{"text":"If they rule upon it, their determination whether it may be wise or unwise in somebody else's opinion is the determination which is effective, so far as the citizens of that State --","start":2619.68,"stop":2632.012,"duration":12.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"With which you have lots of --","start":2632.012,"stop":2633.001,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"-- is -- are concerned.","start":2633.001,"stop":2634.959,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- litigations, lots of litigation whether he did rule upon as I (Inaudible) couldn't determine this thing unless -- it then established that he did rule (Voice Overlap) --","start":2634.959,"stop":2646.579,"duration":11.62}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think it would be --","start":2646.579,"stop":2647.667,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- beyond having satisfied himself of (Inaudible)","start":2647.667,"stop":2651.512,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it -- it --","start":2651.512,"stop":2651.812,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) wouldn't it?","start":2651.812,"stop":2652.75,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it might be necessary to secure an affidavit from him in that -- in that circumstance.","start":2652.75,"stop":2657.696,"duration":4.95},{"text":"Let me point out to the Court the -- the facts as to whether there has been any ruling involved in this National case.","start":2657.696,"stop":2667.886,"duration":10.19},{"text":"Now, this was placed in issue originally.","start":2667.886,"stop":2671.921,"duration":4.03},{"text":"National filed an answer which appears at 11 and 12 of the National record in which it made a claim that under Michigan law, it was fully regulated.","start":2671.921,"stop":2687.324,"duration":15.4},{"text":"The Examiner made a finding in relation to that claim.","start":2687.324,"stop":2691.429,"duration":4.11},{"text":"National doesn't claim that anybody -- any officer of any of the other 47 States regulated to this claim that was regulated by Michigan.","start":2691.429,"stop":2702.159,"duration":10.73},{"text":"The Examiner's finding on that is at record 190 and he states, “Respondent's officials have nothing to show approval of respondent's advertising by the Michigan Insurance Commissioner.\"","start":2702.159,"stop":2716.259,"duration":14.1},{"text":"In any event, it was never submitted to him for approval.","start":2716.259,"stop":2720.475,"duration":4.22},{"text":"Respondent does not submitted the advertising to the Insurance Commissioner of Michigan before it is used.","start":2720.475,"stop":2726.818,"duration":6.34},{"text":"Respondent's business was not inspected by the Insurance Commissioner of the State during the period covered by the complaint which was 1953 and 1954.","start":2726.818,"stop":2736.677,"duration":9.86},{"text":"That finding has not been challenged and when -- National went to the Court of Appeals what it alleged in its petition for review.","start":2736.677,"stop":2746.426,"duration":9.75},{"text":"If he got any claim that it was regulated by Michigan and it alleges on record 214, 45 States including the State of Michigan have an active statutes.","start":2746.426,"stop":2761.974,"duration":15.55},{"text":"That's the basis for their claim that they are regulated.","start":2761.974,"stop":2765.87,"duration":3.9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What I'm -- what I'm trying to search is not their claim but your claim because I should think it's the common experience of every prosecutor and (Inaudible) but the fact that if you don't prosecute doesn't mean approval.","start":2765.87,"stop":2784.909,"duration":19.04},{"text":"It maybe you wait for a rightful change.","start":2784.909,"stop":2787.797,"duration":2.89},{"text":"It may mean this, it may mean that, involving discretion in determination by the responsible officials to act on the law or not without thereby giving him a blue ribbon for excellent procurity.","start":2787.797,"stop":2802.803,"duration":15.01}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I -- I would make -- wish to make clear that we are not suggesting that there must be anything like a formal ruling.","start":2802.803,"stop":2812.826,"duration":10.02},{"text":"We do say that there is an obligation upon the party who claims that the Federal Trade Commission has been divested to show something in the nature of regulation beyond the mere enactment of a statute.","start":2812.826,"stop":2828.296,"duration":15.47}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"How does this all work in the various Sherman law (Inaudible)","start":2828.296,"stop":2836.699,"duration":8.4},{"text":"Those are the other statutes in addition to the Federal State Commission Act.","start":2836.699,"stop":2840.664,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't -- I don't think --","start":2840.664,"stop":2842.013,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap)","start":2842.013,"stop":2842.392,"duration":0.38},{"text":"applies.","start":2842.392,"stop":2843.799,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"There has -- there has been very little litigation on -- insofar as the Sherman Act is concerned because most of the States, it may be almost all of them, have permitted insurance companies to engage in price fixing through rate bureaus.","start":2843.799,"stop":2861.752,"duration":17.95},{"text":"There's a contrary policy and we would not assert that if there is a contrary state policy, there was any room at all under McCarran-Ferguson for federal action, safe to the extent that the McCarran-Ferguson Act itself explicitly provides in Section 4 that the Sherman Act may still be invoked regardless of state legislation where there's coercion, boycott or intimidation.","start":2861.752,"stop":2887.284,"duration":25.53}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, apart from that, I'm -- I'm just wondering what there is of the Sherman Act area under the proviso in 2 (b)?","start":2887.284,"stop":2894.016,"duration":6.73}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it will depend on what the state legislation was, of course, whether the States had policies.","start":2894.016,"stop":2900.162,"duration":6.15},{"text":"Now, in fact, I think state policy -- state policies are not consonant with the Sherman Act, so that leaves very little room.","start":2900.162,"stop":2910.539,"duration":10.38}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That eliminates the Sherman?","start":2910.539,"stop":2911.747,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":2911.747,"stop":2912.236,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That eliminates the Sherman?","start":2912.236,"stop":2913.773,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"It leaves little room.","start":2913.773,"stop":2916.181,"duration":2.41},{"text":"Certainly, the Sherman Act is not eliminated altogether and Section 4 itself shows.","start":2916.181,"stop":2920.933,"duration":4.75}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree, but --","start":2920.933,"stop":2921.593,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2921.593,"stop":2921.982,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- apart from the area covered by Section 4, what is the lesson in 2 (b)?","start":2921.982,"stop":2926.726,"duration":4.74}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it's narrow, but I -- I -- we have not cataloged the -- the State Sherman Acts.","start":2926.726,"stop":2933.129,"duration":6.4},{"text":"We've --","start":2933.129,"stop":2933.178,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":2933.178,"stop":2933.306,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"-- been interested in State Federal Trade Commission Acts.","start":2933.306,"stop":2935.663,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you say the same as Clayton Act?","start":2935.663,"stop":2938.409,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't think this -- my impression at least is that the States do not have on so greatest -- that so -- not so many of the States have statutes comparable to the Clayton Act.","start":2938.409,"stop":2951.908,"duration":13.5},{"text":"It does have States which deal with the matter of rate fixing.","start":2951.908,"stop":2955.866,"duration":3.96},{"text":"I think most of the States have given license to the insurance companies to get together through joint action and fixed rates through their rate bureaus and the like.","start":2955.866,"stop":2967.234,"duration":11.37},{"text":"There have been no federal antitrust cases, so far as I'm aware, involving the insurance business, saved in situations where there has been allegations of boycott, coercion or intimidation.","start":2967.234,"stop":2980.7,"duration":13.47}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We have one of those theories early (Inaudible)","start":2980.7,"stop":2989.777,"duration":9.08},{"text":"So, we have one from the (Inaudible)","start":2989.777,"stop":2991.436,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Co-counsel mentions the New Orleans Insurance case.","start":2991.436,"stop":2996.13,"duration":4.69},{"text":"Now, I'd like to take just a few minutes to go beyond the -- the reports and make brief reference to some of the history as made by those who are in charge of the legislation.","start":2996.13,"stop":3013.496,"duration":17.37},{"text":"This proviso clause that we're concerned with was added in conference.","start":3013.496,"stop":3017.981,"duration":4.49},{"text":"The Conference Report doesn't discuss it, so we are thrown back upon the statements of the sponsors.","start":3017.981,"stop":3025.652,"duration":7.67},{"text":"Now, as it happens, all three of the Senate Conferees did address themselves to the proviso clause during the debates in the Senate.","start":3025.652,"stop":3037.332,"duration":11.68},{"text":"And we have excerpts from each of those three conferee statements at page 58 and the following pages.","start":3037.332,"stop":3050.204,"duration":12.87},{"text":"Senator McCarran's statement appears at 58.","start":3050.204,"stop":3055.218,"duration":5.01},{"text":"We've quoted it there and he points out, “If the States enact legislation,” I'm reading from the second sentence of that quotation, “to the extent that they regulate, they would have taken the business of insurance out from under the Sherman and the Clayton and the other Acts to the extent that they regulate our -- our words which we emphasize and that they again suggest that this use of regulate rather than legislate, regulate rather than enact laws in the proviso clause is not accidental but apparently purposeful.”","start":3055.218,"stop":3095.924,"duration":40.71}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3095.924,"stop":3101.148,"duration":5.22}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If there is some implementation or enforcement, yes.","start":3101.148,"stop":3105.524,"duration":4.38},{"text":"Now, I would distinguish between an active legislation which is self-executing as it were or which carries some immediate criminal penalty and a statute like this Baby Federal Trade Commission Acts which does no more than delegate the authority to regulate and which in and of itself imposes no sanction.","start":3105.524,"stop":3133.667,"duration":28.14},{"text":"We have quoted similarly statements from the two other Senators, both of which emphasized and those are Senators Ferguson and O'Mahoney emphasized that there is to be continued room for federal action.","start":3133.667,"stop":3152.88,"duration":19.21},{"text":"Both of them contemplated that there was to be no regulatory board either because the States couldn't act or because they were not acting.","start":3152.88,"stop":3164.333,"duration":11.45},{"text":"And this same understanding is manifested by President Roosevelt in his statement in signing the Bill where he speaks at page 65 of our brief that after the moratorium, the anti-trust laws and related statutes will be applicable in full force than the effects to the business of insurance except to the extent that the State had assumed the responsibility and are effectively performing that responsibility.","start":3164.333,"stop":3198.735,"duration":34.4},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3198.735,"stop":3199.034,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now.","start":3199.034,"stop":3202.361,"duration":3.33}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 10, 1958","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13535","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 435, Federal Trade Commission versus National Casualty Company, and number 436, Federal Trade Commission versus American Hospital and Life Insurance Company.","start":0,"stop":13.065,"duration":13.07},{"text":"Mr. Langs.","start":13.065,"stop":19.217,"duration":6.15}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and members of the Court.","start":19.217,"stop":22.7,"duration":3.48},{"text":"If it please the Court, I would like to, in the time alloted to me, to bring to your attention certain basic issues which I believe are fundamental to this case.","start":22.7,"stop":41.714,"duration":19.01},{"text":"This case involves a question of federal control of Insurance versus state control of insurance.","start":41.714,"stop":52.98,"duration":11.27},{"text":"We are joined in this position that we present to the Court by 38 States who have joined in the amicus brief, of the State of Michigan.","start":52.98,"stop":63.903,"duration":10.92},{"text":"And there are two amicus briefs that have been filed representing 96% of the Legal Reserve Life Insurance companies of the country and 80% of the accident and health insurance business of the country.","start":63.903,"stop":79.793,"duration":15.89},{"text":"The Federal Trade Commission assumes two positions which we believe are not proper in this case.","start":79.793,"stop":91.285,"duration":11.49},{"text":"It first of all assumes that by innuendo, if not, by direct comment, that the insurance companies operate in this country without control or regulation.","start":91.285,"stop":103.099,"duration":11.81},{"text":"They also apparently assume and I quote from page 29 of their brief which -- and they have used this as a pretext in our opinion for taking the position which they have that there has been widespread evidence that the phenomenal growth of the accident and health insurance business has been accompanied in many instances by false and misleading advertising.","start":103.099,"stop":130.613,"duration":27.51},{"text":"On behalf of the respondent and of the insurance industry of our country, we object to this statement.","start":130.613,"stop":139.105,"duration":8.49},{"text":"There is no evidence of any kind in anyway, shape or form in this case or the National case or in the American Hospital case that there is any of this evidence which counsel referred to, namely thousands of letters which had been received.","start":139.105,"stop":155.722,"duration":16.62},{"text":"Not one of them or any testimony pertaining to that was introduced in our case, whatsoever.","start":155.722,"stop":165.498,"duration":9.78},{"text":"There is no -- there is no complaint on the part of any state agency.","start":165.498,"stop":173.814,"duration":8.32},{"text":"There is no complaint on the part of any officer of any company that they had received any information pertaining to any matter that was deceitful or fraudulent.","start":173.814,"stop":188.968,"duration":15.15},{"text":"Insurance business is built on service, service to the widow, the orphan, the sick, the injured.","start":188.968,"stop":197.293,"duration":8.33},{"text":"It has paid billions of dollars in claims.","start":197.293,"stop":201.026,"duration":3.73},{"text":"It has been in business in this country since the inception of our country.","start":201.026,"stop":206.006,"duration":4.98},{"text":"No business can -- can succeed for long unless it renders service.","start":206.006,"stop":212.605,"duration":6.6},{"text":"Service has been provided by the insurance companies of this country for each score year and more and in the case of National Casualty Company for more than 50 years.","start":212.605,"stop":228.17,"duration":15.56},{"text":"I simply want to indicate at this time our objection to the use of a position which is not a part of this case, which counsel has referred to, so much for that portion.","start":228.17,"stop":241.508,"duration":13.34},{"text":"Now, I believe it is important that we understand a little more fully.","start":241.508,"stop":246.557,"duration":5.05},{"text":"Some of the justices yesterday, I was satisfied, were reaching for some of the material facts and historical background as it might apply to this case.","start":246.557,"stop":257.983,"duration":11.43},{"text":"This Court of course is very familiar with the McCarran Act, how it arrived, how it arose.","start":257.983,"stop":264.494,"duration":6.51},{"text":"In the Southeastern case in 1944, this Court held that the transaction of insurance business constituted interstate commerce.","start":264.494,"stop":276.322,"duration":11.83},{"text":"Prior to this case and from the inception of the -- our constitutional form of government -- government, all insurance business had been regulated, was regulated by the several States, each having a Department of Insurance, each having a budget, each having many personnel.","start":276.322,"stop":297.118,"duration":20.8},{"text":"Without question, I think that the State of New York has probably one of the largest, and probably one of the most substantial insurance departments of any state in the United States.","start":297.118,"stop":318.174,"duration":21.06},{"text":"McCarran-Ferguson Act was adopted in 1945, a few months after the decision of this Court in the Southeastern Underwriter case.","start":318.174,"stop":328.67,"duration":10.5},{"text":"There are three sections of this law which are very important, and the law we believe is very clear.","start":328.67,"stop":337.079,"duration":8.41},{"text":"Counsel for the Government in the several stages that we have gone through before the hearing, the hearing officer for the FTC, Circuit Court of Appeals, the brief here and before this Court has constantly shifted their position.","start":337.079,"stop":354.666,"duration":17.59},{"text":"I can understand to some extent why that would be done, why they'll be necessary because when you run head-on into clear precise language, it takes a little maneuvering to try and get around it.","start":354.666,"stop":367.425,"duration":12.76},{"text":"Section 1 of this McCarran Act provides this that the Congress hereby declares that the continued regulations by the several States of the business of insurance is in the public interest, very clear.","start":367.425,"stop":381.629,"duration":14.2},{"text":"They were stating that the regulation of insurance shall be continued, underlying the word continue.","start":381.629,"stop":392.16,"duration":10.53},{"text":"And the continuous -- continuance of that can only mean and be the continuance of the law as it was applied by the several States.","start":392.16,"stop":400.944,"duration":8.78},{"text":"Section 2 (a) of this law states this.","start":400.944,"stop":404.711,"duration":3.77},{"text":"\"The business of insurance and every person engaged therein shall be subject to the laws of the several States which relate to the regulation of such business.","start":404.711,"stop":414.599,"duration":9.89},{"text":"The business of insurance and every person engaged therein shall be subject to the law of the several States.”","start":414.599,"stop":424.234,"duration":9.63},{"text":"This does not indicate a type of enforcement and I will comment upon that later on, it says the laws.","start":424.234,"stop":431.321,"duration":7.09},{"text":"Section 2 (b) of this Act, which is the passed section which I will poke a portion of it, “No Act of Congress shall be construed to invalidate, impair or supersede any law enacted by any State for the purpose of regulating the business of insurance, unless such Act specifically relates to the business of insurance.”","start":431.321,"stop":455.724,"duration":24.4},{"text":"I don't know how Congress can be more explicit and more clearer than in those three sentences -- three Sections of the law to state that it shall be continued by the States, that it shall be subject to the laws of the States and that no act of Congress shall apply.","start":455.724,"stop":471.917,"duration":16.19},{"text":"Then, they put on the proviso which was added in the conference hearing between the Senate and the House, provided, the Federal Trade Commission, and I'm using only the Federal Trade Commission or others mentioned, as amended shall be applicable to the business of insurance to the extent that such business is not regulated by state law.","start":471.917,"stop":495.848,"duration":23.93},{"text":"I don't see how there can be any question of what Congress -- what Congress intended.","start":495.848,"stop":500.924,"duration":5.08},{"text":"Congress knew, this Court knows and -- and so mentioned in the Prudential-Benjamin case that there are many States and each State would have different ideas about what they would want in the way of regulation.","start":500.924,"stop":514.957,"duration":14.03},{"text":"Congress knew that.","start":514.957,"stop":517.168,"duration":2.21},{"text":"Section 3 (a), provided for a moratorium.","start":517.168,"stop":520.472,"duration":3.3},{"text":"The moratorium simply states that this Act shall not apply until after the moratorium period has expired and then only if the States do not have law.","start":520.472,"stop":533.359,"duration":12.89},{"text":"Now, in the congressional debates that adopted this law, I would like to call attention to three statements and three only.","start":533.359,"stop":544.791,"duration":11.43},{"text":"And I refer to the brief of -- of the Life Insurance Association of America, the amicus brief.","start":544.791,"stop":552.026,"duration":7.23},{"text":"They have it set out fully on page 29, the bottom of page 29 and the top of page 30 and a portion of it and a statement on 31.","start":552.026,"stop":566.6,"duration":14.57},{"text":"And I call the Court's attention to this particular situation as it existed at the time the debate occurred in the United States Senate.","start":566.6,"stop":577.142,"duration":10.54},{"text":"Senator McCarran and Senator Ferguson had indicated very clearly what the law meant and Senator Pepper, I was not satisfied with the statements that it might mean that the law -- the States could adopt laws which the Federal Government or the Federal Trade Commission might believe were not sufficient.","start":577.142,"stop":601.865,"duration":24.72},{"text":"Senator Pepper states this.","start":601.865,"stop":604.101,"duration":2.24},{"text":"I'm referring to and a directing a question to Senator McCarran.","start":604.101,"stop":608.536,"duration":4.43},{"text":"“Does that mean that after January 1, 1948, the States may determine whether or not the Sherman and the other Acts become applicable to the business of insurance?”","start":608.536,"stop":618.37,"duration":9.83},{"text":"Senator McCarran, “The answer to that question is yes.”","start":618.37,"stop":623.923,"duration":5.55},{"text":"Senator Pepper, “Apparently, the conference report goes further than I had understood it to go.","start":623.923,"stop":630.023,"duration":6.1},{"text":"It does not stop with a moratorium at the end of three years.","start":630.023,"stop":634.294,"duration":4.27},{"text":"At the end of three years, the moratorium would continue if in the meantime a State had regulated the business to any extent, whatever.","start":634.294,"stop":642.278,"duration":7.98},{"text":"That would defeat the Supreme Court decision.”","start":642.278,"stop":645.403,"duration":3.13},{"text":"Senator McCarran, “The -- the moratorium would not be continued, but if in the meantime, the States themselves had regulated a business of insurance, the Sherman and Clayton Acts and the other Acts would not become effective.”","start":645.403,"stop":660.875,"duration":15.47},{"text":"One short statement by Senator Ferguson, who of course was one of the sponsors of the Bill, on page 31 of this brief, Senator Ferguson makes this statement.","start":660.875,"stop":671.533,"duration":10.66},{"text":"“After the moratorium has expired, if a State has not legislated on the subjects covered by three Acts,” and underline the word “legislative”, “to which reference has been made, those Acts shall be act applicable to the business of insurance.","start":671.533,"stop":685.517,"duration":13.98},{"text":"But insofar as the State is concerned which has specifically legislated upon the subject, the three Acts shall not apply.","start":685.517,"stop":696.038,"duration":10.52},{"text":"And then Senator Barkley, summing up all of this argument on the last day before this bill was adopted, and this bill came up for decision and then was put over for consideration for one day.","start":696.038,"stop":707.971,"duration":11.93},{"text":"And on page 36, we find his statement that Senator Barkley made and suffice it to state in his very long statement.","start":707.971,"stop":718.106,"duration":10.13},{"text":"But he stated there that Congress still retain the right to consider this matter at a later date if they found that the States were not doing that which Congress felt they should do.","start":718.106,"stop":733.017,"duration":14.91},{"text":"That is some 12 years -- 11 to 12 years ago and there has been no Act in Congress since that time to amend or change that law.","start":733.017,"stop":746.356,"duration":13.34},{"text":"Our --","start":746.356,"stop":746.423,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we gather, there are some States that have not legislated in this field, are they not?","start":746.423,"stop":750.892,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":750.892,"stop":751.623,"duration":0.73},{"text":"All States --","start":751.623,"stop":752.012,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"All States.","start":752.012,"stop":752.272,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"-- have legislated now in different forms.","start":752.272,"stop":755.563,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, on -- on this particular subject --","start":755.563,"stop":757.263,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"On this particular subject, in different forms.","start":757.263,"stop":760.634,"duration":3.37},{"text":"We contend there are -- the Model Bill itself has been adopted by some 40 some States and there are -- and the other States, they have either adopted the new rules and regulations promulgated by the National Association of Insurance Commissioners or they have other laws which are applicable.","start":760.634,"stop":778.497,"duration":17.86},{"text":"So that today, the National Casualty Company which is engaged in the accident and health business and has been admitted to do business in all 48 States, is subject to the jurisdiction of those 48 States to the extent that if we engage in any improper conduct, their license as well as the license of their agents can be revoked.","start":778.497,"stop":800.58,"duration":22.08},{"text":"And there's no question about that, whatsoever.","start":800.58,"stop":804.328,"duration":3.75},{"text":"It's not easy to obtain a license in all 48 States.","start":804.328,"stop":809.192,"duration":4.86},{"text":"It is something that many insurance companies do not obtain.","start":809.192,"stop":814.772,"duration":5.58},{"text":"In the case of National Casualty, they have and have for many years, a license do be business in all 48 States, the District of Columbia and Hawaii.","start":814.772,"stop":824.362,"duration":9.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What's the situation as to the District of Columbia on this subject?","start":824.362,"stop":827.259,"duration":2.9}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"District of Columbia has the Model Bill.","start":827.259,"stop":830.02,"duration":2.76},{"text":"It has a bill specifically which was approved by the President, I think on the 22nd of February, 1958.","start":830.02,"stop":838.689,"duration":8.67},{"text":"That --","start":838.689,"stop":838.872,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"19 what?","start":838.872,"stop":839.496,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"1958, this year.","start":839.496,"stop":844.326,"duration":4.83}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- what is the Model (Voice Overlap) --","start":844.326,"stop":846.663,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"The Model Bill was attached to a copy of it.","start":846.663,"stop":849.272,"duration":2.61},{"text":"You will find attached to the petitioner's brief and you'll also find this copy attached to the American Hospital.","start":849.272,"stop":853.999,"duration":4.73}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean on this sentence, what's the -- what is the provision?","start":853.999,"stop":857.708,"duration":3.71}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"The particular provision?","start":857.708,"stop":862.921,"duration":5.21},{"text":"On page 67 of the respondent's brief, you will find the -- one of the Model Bills which was taken from the State of Kansas, and provides for unfair methods of competition or unfair and deceptive acts or practices which are prohibited, and there, they are listed.","start":862.921,"stop":879.18,"duration":16.26},{"text":"Your Honor does not wish me to read that.","start":879.18,"stop":880.936,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No I just -- that's --","start":880.936,"stop":882.734,"duration":1.8}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":882.734,"stop":883.412,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And this business of advertising is included as one of the facts?","start":883.412,"stop":886.862,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":886.862,"stop":887.644,"duration":0.78},{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, very much so.","start":887.644,"stop":893.386,"duration":5.74},{"text":"The National sells only trough its agents that is licensed in all of the States, and the advertising which it makes up is made up only for agents.","start":893.386,"stop":905.823,"duration":12.44},{"text":"And the advertising material goes to the agents and is disseminated by the agents.","start":905.823,"stop":911.3,"duration":5.48},{"text":"And even to the extent as the record shows, something less than 5% which goes direct to people in a particular State.","start":911.3,"stop":919.898,"duration":8.6},{"text":"It goes there at the request of an agent.","start":919.898,"stop":924.789,"duration":4.89},{"text":"National does not do any direct mail advertising on its own accomplishments.","start":924.789,"stop":929.387,"duration":4.6}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"How many States did you say have the Model Act in percent?","start":929.387,"stop":932.969,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"There are four -- I believe there are 43 or 44 States that have the Model Act at the present time and then more has been adopting more right along.","start":932.969,"stop":942.537,"duration":9.57}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"And how about those that do not have the Model Act?","start":942.537,"stop":946.292,"duration":3.75},{"text":"Are they -- do they adequate people blind for this kind of activity?","start":946.292,"stop":953.331,"duration":7.04}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, very definitely so, very definitely.","start":953.331,"stop":956.81,"duration":3.48}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Every State of the union?","start":956.81,"stop":957.788,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Every state of the union.","start":957.788,"stop":959.364,"duration":1.58},{"text":"If this company engaged in any of practices which we have been charged with here, and that the action was brought by anyone of the States and they found this to be true which they could not under the -- but that fact is not here before this Court.","start":959.364,"stop":974.015,"duration":14.65},{"text":"Our license could be immediately revoked and the license of all of our agents could be immediately revoked in every State, the District of Columbia and Hawaii.","start":974.015,"stop":982.201,"duration":8.19}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you mean in the State where the advertising was disseminated?","start":982.201,"stop":985.958,"duration":3.76}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":985.958,"stop":987.163,"duration":1.21},{"text":"Yes.","start":987.163,"stop":987.95,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What about the mail order?","start":987.95,"stop":989.827,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"We are not a mail order --","start":989.827,"stop":990.812,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand you're not.","start":990.812,"stop":992.196,"duration":1.38},{"text":"I'm -- I'm just finding out what was the scope of your --","start":992.196,"stop":995.846,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Under two decisions which this Court has handed down in the Travelers case in Virginia and the Mcgee case where this Court held and sustained the service of process by mail, against insurance companies engaged in the selling of insurance by mail.","start":995.846,"stop":1012.01,"duration":16.16},{"text":"I think that the -- the State would have definite jurisdiction in those two -- because of those two decisions of this Court.","start":1012.01,"stop":1019.571,"duration":7.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean, a mailing in California or Virginia just outside of each of those States is the basis for this call of a license in those States.","start":1019.571,"stop":1032.905,"duration":13.33}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if I understand, Your Honor, correct, the -- the question was asked to whether or not take the case of Virginia which was the Travelers case and where mail was directed into the State.","start":1032.905,"stop":1046.29,"duration":13.38},{"text":"In that case, this Court sustained an action brought against the company by service of process through the mail.","start":1046.29,"stop":1054.331,"duration":8.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If they excluded, how about the other away around, the mail starting in state one?","start":1054.331,"stop":1059.509,"duration":5.18}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Virginia, going to the State of California?","start":1059.509,"stop":1060.78,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1060.78,"stop":1063.076,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Can Virginia stop that?","start":1063.076,"stop":1064.776,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1064.776,"stop":1065.173,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"The answer is definitely yes.","start":1065.173,"stop":1067.476,"duration":2.3},{"text":"Virginia does not have to permit any of its creatures created by it under law to engage in any deceitful or fraudulent practice.","start":1067.476,"stop":1078.629,"duration":11.15}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose the -- suppose it's not in business in Virginia, but it is in Oregon I should say, and the mail comes out of Virginia.","start":1078.629,"stop":1087.86,"duration":9.23},{"text":"Who would -- who would prevent that?","start":1087.86,"stop":1092.41,"duration":4.55}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there would have to be somebody doing business in Virginia in order for the mail to come out of Virginia and to the extent that there are some --","start":1092.41,"stop":1099.722,"duration":7.31}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it might not be in the insurance business and I suppose it wasn't in the insurance business, selling -- selling insurance in Virgina.","start":1099.722,"stop":1106.553,"duration":6.83},{"text":"The -- the insurance laws of Virgina would not apply.","start":1106.553,"stop":1110.508,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, neither would the Federal Trade Commission law has applied.","start":1110.508,"stop":1113.92,"duration":3.41},{"text":"That gets then into the Silvers case, which is a mail case strictly and purely and simply and not a -- not an FTC or an insurance case.","start":1113.92,"stop":1121.281,"duration":7.36}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, suppose -- suppose that there was false advertising and the Federal Government was taking commerce etcetera.","start":1121.281,"stop":1129.713,"duration":8.43},{"text":"Suppose the -- the false advertising was by television in one State where they were not doing any business and it was going all over the country.","start":1129.713,"stop":1141.715,"duration":12},{"text":"How about the jurisdiction of the -- of the Federal Government in those States where it was not added with the control they regulate?","start":1141.715,"stop":1151.68,"duration":9.97}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, I will not check into the question of television or radio because it is not a part of this decision of this case because --","start":1151.68,"stop":1160.188,"duration":8.51}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"But It would go -- but -- but your rule would prevent the -- the Government in doing the same thing, I would suggest?","start":1160.188,"stop":1166.461,"duration":6.27}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, because our -- the position which we take in our case where we are subject to all the laws of the State.","start":1166.461,"stop":1173.303,"duration":6.84},{"text":"We can be brought to the bar of justice any place, anywhere and we do not do any television or radio advertising.","start":1173.303,"stop":1182.997,"duration":9.69},{"text":"But should we do television or radio advertising, we can be reached in any State of the union or the District of Columbia or Hawaii without any question, whatsoever.","start":1182.997,"stop":1191.944,"duration":8.95}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but there are companies who do not do business in every State in the union, and suppose they -- suppose they did adduce on television in a State of the union where they were not doing business and did went to the -- to the States where they were doing business.","start":1191.944,"stop":1210.976,"duration":19.03},{"text":"Who would -- who would have the regulatory power there?","start":1210.976,"stop":1214.583,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, under -- again, I am engaging in a supposition with the Court because of something I've not checked up, but I think the Travelers case and the Mcgee case probably would offer that State the authority to act if they where actually making sales within that State as a result of the television or radio broadcast.","start":1214.583,"stop":1234.357,"duration":19.77}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean the State where the broadcast originated?","start":1234.357,"stop":1237.422,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1237.422,"stop":1237.669,"duration":0.25},{"text":"Where -- where they received and the sale was made.","start":1237.669,"stop":1240.814,"duration":3.14},{"text":"As long as it's made at a point where the company is located, there's no question about the control.","start":1240.814,"stop":1245.815,"duration":5},{"text":"But if it goes into a State as I understand your question --","start":1245.815,"stop":1249.239,"duration":3.42}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1249.239,"stop":1249.675,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"-- where the company is not doing business and not authorized to do business.","start":1249.675,"stop":1255.408,"duration":5.73}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"That's where the -- that's where the broadcasting has originated.","start":1255.408,"stop":1257.59,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Is received.","start":1257.59,"stop":1259.102,"duration":1.51},{"text":"Well, no, I'm sorry.","start":1259.102,"stop":1260.256,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What I had in mind was, the broadcast originates in a state in which a company is not doing business, but it goes to States in which it is doing business.","start":1260.256,"stop":1272.388,"duration":12.13}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that they would --","start":1272.388,"stop":1273.046,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, who could stop the -- who -- who, under the state laws would regulate that if the State to the broadcasting system or the State of the -- where the insurance business is on.","start":1273.046,"stop":1284.573,"duration":11.53}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, again, prefacing my comment that we have -- do not have that issue here, but it would seems to me that if there's a contract made in the State, it would fall within the legal language which this Court has announced in the two cases I have mention, because there is a contract there even though they're not authorized to do business there.","start":1284.573,"stop":1301.537,"duration":16.96},{"text":"They have it executed and entered into a contract.","start":1301.537,"stop":1303.93,"duration":2.39},{"text":"And ordinarily, a corporation is not permitted to go into a State and engage in a contractual relation, except as it originates outside of the State.","start":1303.93,"stop":1314.401,"duration":10.47},{"text":"So that the both States, conceivably under those circumstances, either States could interpose an objection and obtain a necessary court relief in the federal court or state court.","start":1314.401,"stop":1329.966,"duration":15.56}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I realize that the question I'm asking you is not -- I'm going to ask you not precisely within the scope of your case here (Inaudible)","start":1329.966,"stop":1340.805,"duration":10.84},{"text":"You said that the State where the advertising is disseminated and the mail-order insurance company could get service on them.","start":1340.805,"stop":1349.324,"duration":8.52},{"text":"How could it enforce its order not to do business there, let's say only do it through mail or by mail order?","start":1349.324,"stop":1357.103,"duration":7.78}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think the answer to that, in the Travelers case and in the Mcgee case, this Court held that such an order wasn't forcible against a --","start":1357.103,"stop":1367.361,"duration":10.26}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Held that they could sue on the policy there --","start":1367.361,"stop":1368.953,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1368.953,"stop":1369.236,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- in the Mcgee case.","start":1369.236,"stop":1369.806,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1369.806,"stop":1370.911,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But suppose it issued an order that a mail order has -- did not send anymore false advertising and finding it was false.","start":1370.911,"stop":1382.123,"duration":11.21}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"The federal -- the federal court system covered the entire United States.","start":1382.123,"stop":1387.435,"duration":5.31}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You would say that they could -- the State --","start":1387.435,"stop":1389.596,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"They -- they --","start":1389.596,"stop":1390.089,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the State could go into the federal court and impose it for them.","start":1390.089,"stop":1394.269,"duration":4.18}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Under -- under certain circumstances, yes, definitely.","start":1394.269,"stop":1397.347,"duration":3.08},{"text":"And the federal system covers all the States.","start":1397.347,"stop":1399.866,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Why do you have to draw on the federal courts if --","start":1399.866,"stop":1402.857,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they didn't in the Travelers case, because of an appeal from the Supreme Court of Virginia, directly to this Court.","start":1402.857,"stop":1408.633,"duration":5.78}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But you emphasize that this -- the federal system.","start":1408.633,"stop":1411.559,"duration":2.93},{"text":"I should think it maybe sent from one State into another where -- what you're saying is, what I get out of you is -- mail sense falsely disseminated mail sent from Virginia to New York, there to get business in New York to the satisfaction of the Commissioner of Insurance, Superintended of Insurance in New York.","start":1411.559,"stop":1439.943,"duration":28.38},{"text":"We could say this company is seeking business with fraudulent means in New York and therefore, will stop your business in New York.","start":1439.943,"stop":1448.016,"duration":8.07},{"text":"Why do you have to bother about the federal courts?","start":1448.016,"stop":1449.793,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think under those circumstances you would.","start":1449.793,"stop":1451.995,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"How could he enforce his order against mail orders?","start":1451.995,"stop":1453.64,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"The order -- well, the order -- an order presumably, again --","start":1453.64,"stop":1458.258,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought about that in connection with some of the other cases you have cited.","start":1458.258,"stop":1464.701,"duration":6.44}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"An order of the state court, of course would be subject to a process in any other Court having been entered in the State of New York.","start":1464.701,"stop":1472.728,"duration":8.03},{"text":"It could be removed and transferred as a -- as a cause of action into and be recognized by proper court proceedings in Virginia.","start":1472.728,"stop":1482.027,"duration":9.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if he -- if a company doing business in New York, the Superintendent of Insurance of New York, he goes into the New York Court and enforce an order of exclusion --","start":1482.027,"stop":1491.664,"duration":9.64}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1491.664,"stop":1491.732,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- for doing business in New York.","start":1491.732,"stop":1493.126,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":1493.126,"stop":1494.761,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"How could it enforce the inclusion against the mail-order house?","start":1494.761,"stop":1498.902,"duration":4.14}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as I understand what you are both talking about, that one is talking about something a little different than the other.","start":1498.902,"stop":1505.029,"duration":6.13}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that the order could be issued as against -- as I understand it.","start":1505.029,"stop":1508.775,"duration":3.75}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, because Your Honor --","start":1508.775,"stop":1511.407,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"How could it be enforced?","start":1511.407,"stop":1513.627,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"I think under the Constitution.","start":1513.627,"stop":1514.391,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know that that -- I state very frankly, I don't know if it has -- has any relevance to New York State --","start":1514.391,"stop":1518.924,"duration":4.53}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"It has no right.","start":1518.924,"stop":1519.48,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But it is here.","start":1519.48,"stop":1520.319,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"It has no relevance in here at all.","start":1520.319,"stop":1521.555,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Except in considering the old broad question.","start":1521.555,"stop":1523.803,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- it has no -- it has no relevancy whatsoever in this case and it becomes clearly academic and under the Constitution, the judgment, orders and decrease at one court in -- in a state are to be upheld in the courts of another State where action has been properly taken.","start":1523.803,"stop":1541.472,"duration":17.67},{"text":"It will be recognized when removed and acted upon by another court in another State.","start":1541.472,"stop":1547.399,"duration":5.93}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I should think in New York to everybody's knowledge, that has some very good and some very bad simple tense of the insurance.","start":1547.399,"stop":1555.183,"duration":7.78},{"text":"And I should think that one of the -- an alert superintendent to the insurance will denounce that the ABC Company is engaged in fraudulent representations.","start":1555.183,"stop":1563.68,"duration":8.5},{"text":"It could have a serious effect on the people in New York who will pick up insurance from that question, the lack of insurance.","start":1563.68,"stop":1570.104,"duration":6.42}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I don't think there's any question about that at all.","start":1570.104,"stop":1575.511,"duration":5.41},{"text":"In this case, there is no evidence, not one iota, one word, one scintilla of evidence that is introduced as by any third party in any way, shape or form concerning the deception of any activity by this company.","start":1575.511,"stop":1590.619,"duration":15.11},{"text":"And of course, this company has denied that be enacted.","start":1590.619,"stop":1597.039,"duration":6.42},{"text":"Another interesting point in this case and I'm -- I'll move -- move on.","start":1597.039,"stop":1600.583,"duration":3.54},{"text":"I can probably finish my points.","start":1600.583,"stop":1604.166,"duration":3.58},{"text":"The hearing examiner in this -- before the Federal Trade Commission took the position that the Federal Trade Commission has no jurisdiction in those States where there were laws applicable to this in terms of question.","start":1604.166,"stop":1620.492,"duration":16.33},{"text":"Before the Federal Trade Commission, I think this is important.","start":1620.492,"stop":1624.416,"duration":3.92},{"text":"The Federal Trade Commission took the position that it has jurisdiction irregardless, I'm underlining the word “irregardless”, of state law.","start":1624.416,"stop":1632.223,"duration":7.81},{"text":"It's quite apparent what they were attempting to do and that was to reach fully and completely around the subject matter, irregardless of state law.","start":1632.223,"stop":1641.019,"duration":8.8},{"text":"The Circuit Court of -- before Circuit Court of Appeals, the Federal Trade Commission contended that in the case of conflict between the federal and state law that the federal law would control.","start":1641.019,"stop":1653.402,"duration":12.38},{"text":"And the Circuit Court of course held with the hearing examiner on this jurisdictional question and we are here now on appeal by the Federal Trade Commission.","start":1653.402,"stop":1663.459,"duration":10.06},{"text":"And before the -- before this Court, the petitioner in their brief on page 23, at the top of the page, makes this as the issue, thus the issue before the Court is not whether the Federal Trade Commission can be applied so as to overwrite state policies, specifically expressed either in statutes or administrative action.","start":1663.459,"stop":1686.324,"duration":22.87},{"text":"Congress we think has resolved that issue in the negative.","start":1686.324,"stop":1689.623,"duration":3.3},{"text":"The issue here is quite different, namely whether the Federal Trade Commission can be applied to false insurance, inter -- interstate insurance advertising in the absence of such conflict.","start":1689.623,"stop":1701.28,"duration":11.66},{"text":"Now, they have stated in here that the question about overwriting state policy as determined and set forth in statutes, and I underline the word “statutes” is one of the issues which has been resolved.","start":1701.28,"stop":1718.456,"duration":17.18},{"text":"And yet before this Court, they now take the position which in my humble opinion is a unique position.","start":1718.456,"stop":1724.554,"duration":6.1},{"text":"We state now that the state law is completely effective, providing, we don't get in first and that is the net effect of what they have said if we don't get in first.","start":1724.554,"stop":1738.296,"duration":13.74},{"text":"And if we get in first then res judicata controls.","start":1738.296,"stop":1743.374,"duration":5.08},{"text":"Now, laws are not made on the basis of a footrace and that is exactly the position in which they find themselves as this time.","start":1743.374,"stop":1754.707,"duration":11.33},{"text":"It makes it rather difficult to try and keep up with the changes which they make.","start":1754.707,"stop":1758.67,"duration":3.96},{"text":"A moving target sometimes is difficult to hit.","start":1758.67,"stop":1765.304,"duration":6.63},{"text":"Now, the -- the net result of these positions is this.","start":1765.304,"stop":1780.13,"duration":14.83},{"text":"There are certain fallacious position which the Federal Trade Commission has taken.","start":1780.13,"stop":1785.712,"duration":5.58},{"text":"And I do not want to get into those in detail, Mr. Wheeler who is with me in this case, representing the American Hospital.","start":1785.712,"stop":1791.68,"duration":5.97},{"text":"He's going to talk about that for his portion of the hour.","start":1791.68,"stop":1795.8,"duration":4.12},{"text":"But these positions become fallacious considering the law as Congress has adopted it, as the Senators understood it, as everyone has understood it, except the Federal Trade Commission in its reach for a control over something which has always been controlled by state law and which Congress says shall be continued in the States.","start":1795.8,"stop":1825.938,"duration":30.14}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Langs, might I ask you, what (Inaudible)","start":1825.938,"stop":1846.924,"duration":20.99}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"To the extent that is very clearly defined in my humble opinion, by the statements which I've read from Senator McCarran and Senator Ferguson and Senator Barkley.","start":1846.924,"stop":1857.315,"duration":10.39},{"text":"To the extent that these States have adopted laws, which are applicable to insurance, they shall continue.","start":1857.315,"stop":1866.093,"duration":8.78}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1866.093,"stop":1872.579,"duration":6.49}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"But -- and if it's regulated by a state law, there must be some legislation.","start":1872.579,"stop":1878.164,"duration":5.59},{"text":"As Senator Ferguson said, but so in -- but insofar as the State is concerned which has specifically legislated on the subject matter, the three Acts on my point.","start":1878.164,"stop":1889.802,"duration":11.64}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Has it regulated -- has it regulated in such --","start":1889.802,"stop":1891.379,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"As has specifically legislated, but Senator Ferguson, on the point I'm making is -- Senator Ferguson and Senator McCarran, Senator Barkley, legislation and regulation mean the same thing so far as they were concerned in the adoption of the McCarran Act and can mean nothing else because they were referring specifically to the laws of the several States and they (Voice Overlap) --","start":1891.379,"stop":1915.699,"duration":24.32}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The several States have given power to some agencies regulated in certain ways, have they not?","start":1915.699,"stop":1925.007,"duration":9.31}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"They have given -- they have defined the powers in the same manner as the Federal Trade Commission law defined certain powers.","start":1925.007,"stop":1931.371,"duration":6.36},{"text":"The fact that the Federal Trade Commission says that persons shall not engage in deceptive acts and practices does not give to them or do they go out and put a stamp of approval on everything.","start":1931.371,"stop":1942.131,"duration":10.76},{"text":"They only act, as Justice Frankfurter mentioned yesterday as the prosecutor.","start":1942.131,"stop":1946.525,"duration":4.39},{"text":"They weigh the situation and determine whether or not they should act.","start":1946.525,"stop":1950.388,"duration":3.86},{"text":"And if they decide that they should not act, they do not go then and get a court order, get a Federal Trade Commission order stating that it is all right.","start":1950.388,"stop":1957.581,"duration":7.19},{"text":"Their actions are in the form of prosecution.","start":1957.581,"stop":1960.032,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the difference in effect when the Commerce Clause would give Congress power to regulate interstate commerce?","start":1960.032,"stop":1969.13,"duration":9.1},{"text":"The state laws which give these agencies a power to regulate except to that effect.","start":1969.13,"stop":1974.808,"duration":5.68}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"The Constitution when it says it gives Congress power to regulate, gives power -- gives Congress the power to enact laws.","start":1974.808,"stop":1982.07,"duration":7.26},{"text":"Congress can only speak through its laws.","start":1982.07,"stop":1985.397,"duration":3.33},{"text":"The same thing is true of the State.","start":1985.397,"stop":1987.981,"duration":2.58},{"text":"The State can only speak through its laws in the first instance and then to a department or bureau has allowed them to set up certain regulations within the framework of the law which it has adopted, but there must first be the law.","start":1987.981,"stop":2003.007,"duration":15.03}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is your argument basically that the States having undertaken to regulate to this extent, that we should construe it somewhat as we have in certain N.L.R.B. cases and others to the effect that the State having indicated its desire to regulate to this extent as negative to any implication that it desires to have it regulated anymore.","start":2003.007,"stop":2034.856,"duration":31.85}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":2034.856,"stop":2035.562,"duration":0.71},{"text":"I think that that is a fair statement of it in the -- of course, there is the N.L.R.B. situation.","start":2035.562,"stop":2044.013,"duration":8.45},{"text":"There is a dispute as to the question of which item shall be handled before the N.L.R.B. in which shall belong to the State, where they -- where they shall regulate.","start":2044.013,"stop":2053.5,"duration":9.49},{"text":"That is not clearly defined even today.","start":2053.5,"stop":2056.516,"duration":3.02},{"text":"In this situation, however, it is clearly defined and the Congress says that no act of Congress shall take effect or supersede an Act of the State.","start":2056.516,"stop":2067.068,"duration":10.55},{"text":"Now, there is that difference where the --","start":2067.068,"stop":2069.391,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It's that -- it's that difference if you are right in saying that regulation as here, means any legislation which the State passed?","start":2069.391,"stop":2076.55,"duration":7.16}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"Any legislation that is applicable to insurance.","start":2076.55,"stop":2079.135,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2079.135,"stop":2079.395,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"John F. Langs","textObjs":[{"text":"It must be applicable to insurance of course.","start":2079.395,"stop":2083.936,"duration":4.54},{"text":"Thank you, Your Honor, I would like to leave the rest of my time for Mr. Wheeler.","start":2083.936,"stop":2095.728,"duration":11.79}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Wheeler.","start":2095.728,"stop":2098.265,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":2098.265,"stop":2104.446,"duration":6.18},{"text":"In spite of the fact that the only question before this Court is a question of jurisdiction of counsel for petitioner on yesterday entered into the merits of the case, which seem to me were the obvious purpose of attempting to convince this Court that my client was a bad actor and that my client had progressed through misrepresentation and control.","start":2104.446,"stop":2136.487,"duration":32.04},{"text":"Before getting into the question before this Court therefore, it seems to me that I would be justified in very briefly replying to that position taken by counsel for the petitioner.","start":2136.487,"stop":2151.516,"duration":15.03},{"text":"When the hearing was had in our case, every State in which my client did business, except the State of Mississippi had enacted regulatory law.","start":2151.516,"stop":2166.914,"duration":15.4},{"text":"It had not been enacted in the State of Mississippi.","start":2166.914,"stop":2170.496,"duration":3.58},{"text":"After an extensive hearing, the hearing examiner held that in all States except Mississippi, the Federal Trade Commission had no jurisdiction.","start":2170.496,"stop":2185.197,"duration":14.7},{"text":"But as the law had not been enacted, in the State of Mississippi, it had jurisdiction in that State.","start":2185.197,"stop":2193.087,"duration":7.89},{"text":"And he then went very extensively into the charges in the complaint, and I wish to address myself very briefly to that.","start":2193.087,"stop":2207.195,"duration":14.11},{"text":"I'll just take one instance in the complaint with which he dealt and I'll say that the hearing examiner exonerated my client completely and held that it had not been guilty of any false, fraudulent or deceptive practices.","start":2207.195,"stop":2224.302,"duration":17.11},{"text":"Just one instance of the complaint, one item the complaint was based on the charge that in our advertising, we had the statement, “covers accidents”.","start":2224.302,"stop":2241.974,"duration":17.67},{"text":"The hearing examiner in his -- his initial decision and all of these are in the record.","start":2241.974,"stop":2248.411,"duration":6.44},{"text":"The hearing examiner pointed out the fact that in that complaint and they -- the Federal Trade Commission took the position that that was a representation, that all accidents were covered.","start":2248.411,"stop":2263.128,"duration":14.72},{"text":"The hearing examiner pointed out the fact that the Federal Trade Commission in filing the complaint had stopped at a comma in a sentence and that the statement in the advertising was “Covers accident, subject to policy terms.”","start":2263.128,"stop":2282.192,"duration":19.06},{"text":"And in the same advertising, there was the statement in 12-point boldface type.","start":2282.192,"stop":2290.936,"duration":8.74},{"text":"“Benefits are subjects to the terms of the policy issues.”","start":2290.936,"stop":2297.115,"duration":6.18},{"text":"The hearing examiner under the undisputed evidence stated that these brochures were sent only to agents and became a part of the agent sale kit and were only used in personal interviews with prospects.","start":2297.115,"stop":2320.118,"duration":23},{"text":"And he took the position that in that personal interview, that when the advertising stated, covered -- covers accidents subject to policy terms that the prospect would naturally think of two things.","start":2320.118,"stop":2339.643,"duration":19.53},{"text":"One was that accident insurance always had some exceptions and the other was, when the flag was raised, subject to policy terms that the prospect would inquire as to what were the exceptions in what accidents were not covered.","start":2339.643,"stop":2358.946,"duration":19.3}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What wasn't -- what accidents were covered in your policy, Mr. Wheeler?","start":2358.946,"stop":2363.201,"duration":4.26}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the accidents as the -- as the -- in the usual policy.","start":2363.201,"stop":2369.14,"duration":5.94},{"text":"It was provided that the accident had to be by external and violent means.","start":2369.14,"stop":2374.688,"duration":5.55}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon?","start":2374.688,"stop":2375.365,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"Had to be external and violent means as practically all policies of accidents insurance provide.","start":2375.365,"stop":2384.398,"duration":9.03},{"text":"And provided that if the accidental death was brought about by self-destruction either while sane or insane, that was not covered, just the -- the normal exceptions in an accident policy and those were the terms that were referred to when it said subject to policy terms.","start":2384.398,"stop":2407.945,"duration":23.55},{"text":"Now, the -- the share --","start":2407.945,"stop":2410.208,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What point -- what point did the Government raise on that, that it did not cover this other ones (Voice Overlap) --","start":2410.208,"stop":2415.773,"duration":5.57}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the Government took the position, Mr. Chief Justice, that for this not to be deceptive advertising that it was necessary for every limitation of the policy to be set out verbatim in all of the advertising.","start":2415.773,"stop":2437.837,"duration":22.06},{"text":"In other words, all of the exceptions would have to be limited and that the place in their subject to this policy terms was not sufficient.","start":2437.837,"stop":2447.505,"duration":9.67},{"text":"That was the position they took.","start":2447.505,"stop":2449.924,"duration":2.42},{"text":"Now, the -- the hearing examiners, this appears on page 58 of the record.","start":2449.924,"stop":2460.772,"duration":10.85},{"text":"The allegations of the complaint charging the respondent with making false and misleading statements and representations with respect to the terms and conditions of its policies in general or with respect to the terms and conditions of specific policies have not been established by a substantial, reliable probative evidence.","start":2460.772,"stop":2483.694,"duration":22.92},{"text":"Accordingly, it cannot be found that the respondent has violated the Federal Trade Commission Act by engaging in unfair and deceptive acts and practices in commerce to the prejudice and injury of the public.","start":2483.694,"stop":2497.495,"duration":13.8},{"text":"Therefore, it is ordered that the complaint herein be in the same, is hereby dismissed.","start":2497.495,"stop":2504.374,"duration":6.88},{"text":"On appeal, the -- the Federal Trade Commission held that the charges in the complaint had been established and issued a cease and desist order.","start":2504.374,"stop":2518.896,"duration":14.52},{"text":"Now -- proceeding now to the merits of the case, counsel for petitioner refers to these enactments by the States, as little Trade Commission Acts.","start":2518.896,"stop":2540.735,"duration":21.84},{"text":"Now, of course, living why -- where I do, it's -- would be a little difficult for me to admit that anything relative to Texas was little.","start":2540.735,"stop":2549.457,"duration":8.72},{"text":"But without being at all facetious, I wish to submit to the Court that all of these Acts are solemn enactments by the State legislators and that they are entitled to the same dignity as the Federal Trade Commission Act.","start":2549.457,"stop":2575.404,"duration":25.95},{"text":"Counsel takes the position that these Acts are permissive.","start":2575.404,"stop":2579.984,"duration":4.58},{"text":"And therefore, the Insurance Commissioners can enforce them or refrain from enforcing them just as he desires.","start":2579.984,"stop":2589.311,"duration":9.33},{"text":"All of these Insurance Commissioners are officers of the State under oath to enforce the laws that are in their charge.","start":2589.311,"stop":2599.197,"duration":9.89},{"text":"And I wish to call the Court's attention to two provisions of this Act, one of which is attached to the petitioner's brief and one to our brief.","start":2599.197,"stop":2615.044,"duration":15.85},{"text":"I call the Court's attention to page -- pages 34 and 41 of our brief, the appendix, which shows clearly that these Acts are not permissive Acts but they are mandatory upon the officer in charge with the duty.","start":2615.044,"stop":2633.931,"duration":18.89}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"This is the state law.","start":2633.931,"stop":2635.265,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"This is the state law.","start":2635.265,"stop":2636.227,"duration":0.96},{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2636.227,"stop":2637.119,"duration":0.89},{"text":"On page 34, a person is defined as any individual, corporation, association, partnership reciprocally exchanged enter insurer, lodge insurer, fraternal benefits society and any other legal entity engaged in the business of insurance including agents, brokers and adjusters.","start":2637.119,"stop":2658.383,"duration":21.26},{"text":"Now, changing -- turning to page 41, under the heading “Power of Commissioner,” the Commissioner have -- shall have power to examine and investigate into the affairs of every person engaged in the business of insurance in this State in order to determine whether such person has been or is engaged in any unfair method of competition or in any unfair deceptive act or practice prohibited by Section 3.","start":2658.383,"stop":2688.078,"duration":29.7},{"text":"And then, in the next paragraph, this shows it is not permissive.","start":2688.078,"stop":2694.229,"duration":6.15},{"text":"Whenever the Commissioner shall have reason to believe that any person has been engaged or is engaging in this State, in any unfair method of competition or any unfair or deceptive act or practice defined in Section 4, and that a proceeding by him in respect thereto, would be to the interest of the public.","start":2694.229,"stop":2720.876,"duration":26.65},{"text":"He shall issue and serve upon such person a statement of the charges and so forth.","start":2720.876,"stop":2727.5,"duration":6.62}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this -- are these three from a uniform law that was enacted by --","start":2727.5,"stop":2732.435,"duration":4.93}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2732.435,"stop":2734.228,"duration":1.79},{"text":"Sir?","start":2734.228,"stop":2735.082,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Was it -- are these provisions you were just reading from a uniform law applied --","start":2735.082,"stop":2739.655,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2739.655,"stop":2740.287,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- adopted by all the States?","start":2740.287,"stop":2741.49,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"So called, not by all of them.","start":2741.49,"stop":2743.999,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"How many?","start":2743.999,"stop":2745.596,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe, Mr. Lang said 43 States.","start":2745.596,"stop":2748.347,"duration":2.75}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"43.","start":2748.347,"stop":2748.693,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"And that in the other States, there were similar Acts, but what the -- the so-called Model Code was adopted in 43 States.","start":2748.693,"stop":2764.325,"duration":15.63},{"text":"I think therefore that the charge which is not based as I see it on any foundation of fact whatsoever that these State Commissioners are not doing anything about this matter, is entirely uncalled for.","start":2764.325,"stop":2782.629,"duration":18.3},{"text":"As far back as 1944, the time of the South Eastern decision which of course was before these Model Acts had been enacted but when the -- the States have been regulating insurance for many years, Mr. Justice Jackson in his dissent made this statement.","start":2782.629,"stop":2806.136,"duration":23.51},{"text":"\"The States began nearly a century ago to regulate insurance.","start":2806.136,"stop":2811.279,"duration":5.14},{"text":"And State regulation, while no doubt of even -- of uneven quality is a successful going concern.","start":2811.279,"stop":2819.497,"duration":8.22},{"text":"Several States where the greatest volume of insurance is transacted have rigorous and enlightened legislation with enforcement and supervision in the hands of experienced and competent officials.\"","start":2819.497,"stop":2834.349,"duration":14.85},{"text":"And now, that these so called Model Acts have been passed, I think that we must assume that these sworn officers of the State -- of the States who have the interest of the citizens of their State at heart to see that they are not imposed upon, to see that they are not defrauded.","start":2834.349,"stop":2858.654,"duration":24.3},{"text":"I think we must certainly presume that they will be as diligent and as conscientious in the enforcement of their laws as the Federal Trade Commission is in the enforcement of the federal law.","start":2858.654,"stop":2873.664,"duration":15.01},{"text":"And I think it's uncalled for without any foundation of fact to say that these laws are not being enforced.","start":2873.664,"stop":2880.317,"duration":6.65},{"text":"While I think the position that it doesn't turn on the enforcement of the law, the power to the States is given by the enactment of the law.","start":2880.317,"stop":2890.286,"duration":9.97}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It certainly doesn't turn of it on our belief, the reference whether the State is doing a good job.","start":2890.286,"stop":2896.027,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir, I don't --","start":2896.027,"stop":2896.654,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"We don't have to decide that one with the other here.","start":2896.654,"stop":2899.134,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2899.134,"stop":2901.849,"duration":2.72},{"text":"Now, it seems to me that this language to the extent that such business is not regulated by state law, cannot be tortured as they would attempt to torture it to mean to the extent that an adequate state regulatory law is being enforced by the States.","start":2901.849,"stop":2928.516,"duration":26.67}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you mean by adequate in your statement?","start":2928.516,"stop":2930.771,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":2930.771,"stop":2931.654,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you mean by the use of the word adequate if you would say what this adequacy means in the business of (Inaudible)","start":2931.654,"stop":2940.47,"duration":8.82}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think I -- I think I could leave the -- the adequate out.","start":2940.47,"stop":2943.984,"duration":3.51},{"text":"I think when we read -- when we read these Model Acts, I think it is clear that they are adequate.","start":2943.984,"stop":2951.819,"duration":7.84},{"text":"Now then, coming to the -- coming onto the --","start":2951.819,"stop":2953.758,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":2953.758,"stop":2954.826,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry?","start":2954.826,"stop":2955.4,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Again, do you have to depend on that to say that they are adequate?","start":2955.4,"stop":2960.111,"duration":4.71},{"text":"Maybe their acts are wholly adequate, insofar as laying out a plan of future regulation is concerned but does that mean that we have to decide that they are either wholly adequate or not wholly adequate?","start":2960.111,"stop":2976.21,"duration":16.1}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't -- I don't think so, except that I think that these laws where it states and I will apply it before I close, I will apply it to -- to my case.","start":2976.21,"stop":2987.868,"duration":11.66},{"text":"That in our case, there is no extent to which the law is not regulated by the -- our Acts are not regulated by state law.","start":2987.868,"stop":2998.831,"duration":10.96},{"text":"Now, what occurs to me is, if --","start":2998.831,"stop":3001.857,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- that raises something I didn't know was here.","start":3001.857,"stop":3005.832,"duration":3.97},{"text":"Have -- have the States where you do business, provided actual machinery -- not merely provided machinery, but in the actual effect, releasing the type of advertising that your company does?","start":3005.832,"stop":3024.181,"duration":18.35}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think that's necessary.","start":3024.181,"stop":3025.49,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that but I --","start":3025.49,"stop":3026.493,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3026.493,"stop":3026.848,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I thought you were saying ahead.","start":3026.848,"stop":3028.285,"duration":1.44},{"text":"I was in --","start":3028.285,"stop":3029.136,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3029.136,"stop":3029.544,"duration":0.41},{"text":"I didn't -- didn't mean to say it.","start":3029.544,"stop":3031.083,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I beg your pardon.","start":3031.083,"stop":3031.998,"duration":0.91},{"text":"I misunderstood you.","start":3031.998,"stop":3032.019,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3032.019,"stop":3033.566,"duration":1.55},{"text":"Now, what occurs to me is, if the Government is right in this matter, who would determine -- who would determine as to whether these laws were being enforced or not, the state laws?","start":3033.566,"stop":3049.368,"duration":15.8},{"text":"Would the Federal Trade Commission determine it?","start":3049.368,"stop":3052.62,"duration":3.25},{"text":"We have a case in which an insurance company does business in 43 States, in the 43 States in which these Model Laws have been passed.","start":3052.62,"stop":3064.642,"duration":12.02},{"text":"Now then, they bring a complaint against this company.","start":3064.642,"stop":3070.432,"duration":5.79},{"text":"If they are correct, they have no jurisdiction where the law is being enforced.","start":3070.432,"stop":3080.091,"duration":9.66},{"text":"It would seem to me therefore, in every case, the question of jurisdiction would not depend on the state of the law.","start":3080.091,"stop":3089.331,"duration":9.24},{"text":"But in every case, if they are correct, would depend on whether the law was being enforced in each one of these States.","start":3089.331,"stop":3098.771,"duration":9.44},{"text":"So, in each case, in each case where a complaint had been filed, there would first have to be determined the question of -- of jurisdiction as to whether the law was being enforced, or whether the law was not being enforced.","start":3098.771,"stop":3114.372,"duration":15.6},{"text":"Now, what quantum -- what quantum of enforcement would be necessary according to them to give jurisdiction and how -- how would that be determined?","start":3114.372,"stop":3126.805,"duration":12.43},{"text":"And then, there's the followed proposition.","start":3126.805,"stop":3129.739,"duration":2.93},{"text":"It seems to be the set law that the question of jurisdiction is not determined by whether they have jurisdiction at the time the complaint is filed.","start":3129.739,"stop":3139.951,"duration":10.21},{"text":"But as in our case, when the complaint was filed, the law had not been passed by Mississippi.","start":3139.951,"stop":3147.406,"duration":7.45},{"text":"Before the hearing, before the Commission, the law had been enacted by Mississippi.","start":3147.406,"stop":3151.418,"duration":4.01},{"text":"So, in all of the States in which we did business, the law had been enacted.","start":3151.418,"stop":3157.068,"duration":5.65},{"text":"Now then, suppose in this case, after they had determined that the law had not been enforced in any of these States and therefore, they had jurisdiction.","start":3157.068,"stop":3168.319,"duration":11.25},{"text":"Supposed during the pendency of that case, the -- some State began to enforce the law.","start":3168.319,"stop":3176.35,"duration":8.03},{"text":"So then, the question of jurisdiction would have to be determined at the time that they entered the order, then they would have no jurisdiction of the State that had began to enforce the law after the -- after the hearing had proceeded.","start":3176.35,"stop":3191.646,"duration":15.3},{"text":"It just seems to me that Congress could not have had any such idea in mind and --","start":3191.646,"stop":3202.992,"duration":11.35}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Wheeler, at the time -- at the time this complaint was filed against you.","start":3202.992,"stop":3207.612,"duration":4.62},{"text":"There was no law in Mississippi.","start":3207.612,"stop":3209.781,"duration":2.17},{"text":"Did -- did the Federal Trade Commission have jurisdiction then?","start":3209.781,"stop":3217.408,"duration":7.63}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm inclined to believe it did --","start":3217.408,"stop":3218.728,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3218.728,"stop":3218.912,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"-- as far as Mississippi was concerned.","start":3218.912,"stop":3219.831,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, as far as Mississippi was concerned.","start":3219.831,"stop":3222.144,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3222.144,"stop":3222.391,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"There's no question about that --","start":3222.391,"stop":3223.098,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3223.098,"stop":3223.378,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that they wouldn't act.","start":3223.378,"stop":3224.997,"duration":1.62},{"text":"And it was only the -- only the passage, subsequent passage of the Act which diverse to the Government of jurisdiction.","start":3224.997,"stop":3232.495,"duration":7.5}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that is our position.","start":3232.495,"stop":3233.255,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes.","start":3233.255,"stop":3237.236,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"Now then, I wish to refer very briefly, I haven't seen one of these lights come on yet.","start":3237.236,"stop":3243.447,"duration":6.21},{"text":"I -- I may have missed it.","start":3243.447,"stop":3245.454,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"The white one will come on when you have five minutes left --","start":3245.454,"stop":3247.882,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3247.882,"stop":3248.422,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and the red one when you are finished.","start":3248.422,"stop":3249.773,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3249.773,"stop":3253.53,"duration":3.76},{"text":"Now, I think that that is born out by the -- the report, the fact, the position that we take that it isn't the enactment of the law.","start":3253.53,"stop":3263.432,"duration":9.9},{"text":"I think that is born out by the report of the Senate Judiciary Committee at the time that the moratorium was -- was extended for six months, and that appears in our brief on page 31.","start":3263.432,"stop":3284.472,"duration":21.04},{"text":"Now, I think it's quite significant.","start":3284.472,"stop":3288.246,"duration":3.77},{"text":"This bill -- this is the report of the Senate Committee on the judiciary as to the proposed amendment to extend the moratorium, six months.","start":3288.246,"stop":3297.509,"duration":9.26},{"text":"This bill extends to so-called moratorium --","start":3297.509,"stop":3298.905,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"In -- in your brief, on what page, 31?","start":3298.905,"stop":3301.617,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"J. D. Wheeler","textObjs":[{"text":"31 of our brief.","start":3301.617,"stop":3306.654,"duration":5.04},{"text":"This bill extends the so-called moratorium provision of Public Law of 15 of the 79th legislature, from January 1, 1948 until June 30th, 1948.","start":3306.654,"stop":3319.252,"duration":12.6},{"text":"The Committee is informed and is satisfied that an effort has been exerted by the insurance industry, the Insurance Commissioners and the States in dealing with the matter of state regulation.","start":3319.252,"stop":3331.132,"duration":11.88},{"text":"However, the Committee recognizes that the problems have not been solved and is all the opinion that an extension of the so-called moratorium should be granted in order to provide the Congress an additional time to examine into the situation more completely than it has been able to do during the present session.","start":3331.132,"stop":3351.293,"duration":20.16},{"text":"As the Committee is of the opinion that considerable studies should be given to this matter and the question of the need, if any, of further federal legislation.","start":3351.293,"stop":3364.225,"duration":12.93},{"text":"It would appear most desirable to extend this moratorium period an additional six months, therefore, giving -- thereby, giving the Congress a reasonable time to examine the developments have -- that have taken place in this field during and immediately subsequent to the meetings of the 1947 legislatures.","start":3364.225,"stop":3386.258,"duration":22.03},{"text":"Now then, the 1947 legislatures could only enact regulatory laws.","start":3386.258,"stop":3393.382,"duration":7.12},{"text":"Now, I point out that nearly 10 years has passed since that report was made and that apparently, the state regulation is satisfactory to the Congress because they have not found the need of any additional federal legislation.","start":3393.382,"stop":3412.772,"duration":19.39},{"text":"Of course, we know at anytime, and we take the position that this proposition of adequacy of enforcement is not in the province of the Federal Trade Commission but it is in the province of the Congress of the United States at anytime that the Congress of the United States is dissatisfied with the way the state laws are being enforced.","start":3412.772,"stop":3437.443,"duration":24.67},{"text":"They can set up adequate federal laws and set up adequate federal legislation and take over this entire proposition of the regulation of insurance.","start":3437.443,"stop":3448.84,"duration":11.4},{"text":"Of course, this proposition of advertising is a very small segment of this regulation.","start":3448.84,"stop":3455.358,"duration":6.52},{"text":"And we submit that it is apparent that the present situation over a period of 10 years since the Committee said they would engage in that study has been satisfactory to the Congress of the United States, which is the body to pass on whether this job is being done or not.","start":3455.358,"stop":3479.356,"duration":24},{"text":"Now, in our case, we do no mail-order business, we do no magazine or newspaper advertising, we do no radio or television advertising, we do no direct mail advertising of any kind.","start":3479.356,"stop":3499.459,"duration":20.1},{"text":"These brochures are merely sent to our agents in their sealed kit to be presented in face-to-face interviews with the prospects.","start":3499.459,"stop":3514.933,"duration":15.47},{"text":"If they disseminate any advertising, which is objectionable in every State where we do business, cease and desist orders may be issued against us.","start":3514.933,"stop":3532.523,"duration":17.59},{"text":"Heavy fines maybe imposed upon us because the law provides for heavy fines and the license, both of the company and of every agent, may be rescinded by the state authorities.","start":3532.523,"stop":3546.25,"duration":13.73},{"text":"We therefore submit, that in our case, there is no extent to which our business in not regulated by state law.","start":3546.25,"stop":3557.137,"duration":10.89},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3557.137,"stop":3560.694,"duration":3.56}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Spritzer.","start":3560.694,"stop":3562.509,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":3562.509,"stop":3567.533,"duration":5.02},{"text":"Mr. Lang, in dealing with the legislative history, referred the Court to a passage taken from Senator McCarran's comments when he was dealing specifically with the 2 (b) proviso.","start":3567.533,"stop":3587.695,"duration":20.16},{"text":"And he quoted that passage from page 30 of the brief for the Life Insurance Association.","start":3587.695,"stop":3597.352,"duration":9.66},{"text":"And he read a question which began on 29 from Senator Pepper, \"Does that mean after January 1, 1948, the States may determine whether or not the Sherman and the other Acts become applicable?\"","start":3597.352,"stop":3613.202,"duration":15.85},{"text":"And he also read the first sentence of the reply, namely, the answer to that question is yes.","start":3613.202,"stop":3621.513,"duration":8.31},{"text":"From that, he draws the inference that notwithstanding the use of the word “regulated” in the proviso, the Court should treat the language of the proviso as if Congress has -- had said if the States enact a law.","start":3621.513,"stop":3638.12,"duration":16.61},{"text":"However, I suggest one should also read the second sentence of Senator McCarran's reply to that question, and that reads.","start":3638.12,"stop":3647.651,"duration":9.53},{"text":"“During the three-year moratorium, the States may if they see fit to do so, enact legislation for the purpose of regulation.”","start":3647.651,"stop":3659.415,"duration":11.76},{"text":"And then he says, I think making the thought still more clear, “If they do enact such legislation to the extent that they regulate, they will have taken the business of insurance out from under the Federal Acts.”","start":3659.415,"stop":3673.762,"duration":14.35},{"text":"Now, I find it difficult to read that passage to support the conclusion that legislation in the form of a general enabling statute is equivalent to regulation.","start":3673.762,"stop":3687.257,"duration":13.49},{"text":"I think it leads to an opposite inference.","start":3687.257,"stop":3693.545,"duration":6.29},{"text":"Now, I would like to emphasize --","start":3693.545,"stop":3695.18,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Might I ask, Mr. Spritzer.","start":3695.18,"stop":3696.941,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3696.941,"stop":3697.051,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you mind saying a few words about the -- the mail-fraud statute, whether or not the -- there could lie a federal indictment for -- not necessarily in these cases but where there is fraud in the use of the mails in sending advertising material by insurance companies.","start":3697.051,"stop":3719.041,"duration":21.99},{"text":"Would that lie today after the McCarran Act?","start":3719.041,"stop":3722.974,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"I certainly think so.","start":3722.974,"stop":3725.228,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think that stands on a -- is that a clear case in the Federal Trade Commission Act?","start":3725.228,"stop":3731.415,"duration":6.19},{"text":"I don't think the McCarran Act mentions the mail fraud, doesn't it?","start":3731.415,"stop":3733.513,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":3733.513,"stop":3734.015,"duration":0.5},{"text":"It doesn't specifically, but I would assume that the federal control over the mail says -- have sifted in the Sylvanus case which we did cite in our brief.","start":3734.015,"stop":3743.65,"duration":9.64}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that the Seventh Circuit case?","start":3743.65,"stop":3745.948,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Decided that question, it was the Seventh Circuit case.","start":3745.948,"stop":3748.773,"duration":2.83},{"text":"I would like to point out, however, that --","start":3748.773,"stop":3751.123,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"They decided that in favor of the federal --","start":3751.123,"stop":3752.891,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"They held the criminal statute apply.","start":3752.891,"stop":3755.093,"duration":2.2},{"text":"Now, of course, that's no substitute for the Federal Trade Commission Act.","start":3755.093,"stop":3758.44,"duration":3.35},{"text":"That's a criminal statute and it involves fraud, much advertising maybe misleading or deceptive and not involve fraud, do not involve the kind of intent that one would have to prove in a criminal case.","start":3758.44,"stop":3771.858,"duration":13.42},{"text":"Moreover, in a criminal case, we have the burden of ruling beyond a reasonable doubt and so forth.","start":3771.858,"stop":3780.249,"duration":8.39},{"text":"We feel that the Federal Trade Commission Act is needed because it's a prophylactic act and the criminal statutes furnish no substitute.","start":3780.249,"stop":3788.994,"duration":8.75},{"text":"Now, the mail-order problem is not involved in this case.","start":3788.994,"stop":3794.625,"duration":5.63},{"text":"The Court, I think properly may have some concern with that because of its close relationship and it is in our view, a serious question.","start":3794.625,"stop":3806.022,"duration":11.4},{"text":"And the problem arises, I think typically, where an insurance company incorporates in a single State, say the State in Nebraska.","start":3806.022,"stop":3815.339,"duration":9.32},{"text":"It doesn't get a license in any other State but it sends out its advertising materials by mail.","start":3815.339,"stop":3824.098,"duration":8.76},{"text":"And those who decide, they wish to buy a policy, fill out a form and send it back.","start":3824.098,"stop":3830.874,"duration":6.78},{"text":"It would seem to me that the other 47 States are probably powerless to deal with that situation.","start":3830.874,"stop":3840.282,"duration":9.41},{"text":"I don't see how there could be any enforcement if the State -- if the other States did enter a cease and desist order against sending the mails into the States how they could possibly enforce it.","start":3840.282,"stop":3853.134,"duration":12.85},{"text":"And indeed, in the Travelers Health case, the Court had its doubts about the problem of enforcement, at least where it extended beyond the question of service of process.","start":3853.134,"stop":3866.576,"duration":13.44},{"text":"And Justice Douglas's concurring opinion observed that in the case of a truly mail-order operation, the States are utterly helpless.","start":3866.576,"stop":3876.336,"duration":9.76},{"text":"Now, the --","start":3876.336,"stop":3877.109,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In the -- yet, even as to that kind of jurisdiction which you claim, the Federal Trade Commission would have had no jurisdiction whatever during the moratorium period, would it?","start":3877.109,"stop":3887.574,"duration":10.47}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right and that was a very special provision which was designed by Congress to permit a reorientation of the whole picture and to give the insurance companies as Congress said, a breathing spell.","start":3887.574,"stop":3902.326,"duration":14.75}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Even though it was contemplated that after the moratorium ended, this jurisdiction still subsist with your documents, despite the passage of state laws?","start":3902.326,"stop":3911.946,"duration":9.62}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3911.946,"stop":3912.205,"duration":0.26},{"text":"I think -- I think there's no question that Congress proposed that there be jurisdiction where the States could not act.","start":3912.205,"stop":3920.773,"duration":8.57},{"text":"That is very emphatically brought out in passages which are at pages 1661 of our brief from Senators Ferguson and O'Malley.","start":3920.773,"stop":3930.951,"duration":10.18},{"text":"Our further question, it seems to me, is whether there is no regulation -- excuse me.Whether there is no federal jurisdiction, where the States could concededly regulate under statutes already on the books of the States, but have failed to do so.","start":3930.951,"stop":3951.21,"duration":20.26},{"text":"Now, a word about this matter of failure to regulate.","start":3951.21,"stop":3954.568,"duration":3.36},{"text":"We have a brief by the State of Michigan signed by 25 other States.","start":3954.568,"stop":3959.878,"duration":5.31},{"text":"I'm not going to deal with the points that that brief makes because I think that the entire brief misconceives the extent of the jurisdiction which we are claiming and that the opposition is based upon a misconception.","start":3959.878,"stop":3973.668,"duration":13.79},{"text":"But what does that briefs state, as to what the States are or are not doing by way of regulation?","start":3973.668,"stop":3981.424,"duration":7.76},{"text":"Here is a brief signed by the Attorney Generals of 26 States, which does not cite a single specific ruling or determination as to the advertising practices of a single insurer, which does not refer to the institution of a single cease and desist proceeding and is unable to refer to a single case, having arisen in the state courts.","start":3981.424,"stop":4008.423,"duration":27},{"text":"I don't want to leave the impression that we are in opposition to the States.","start":4008.423,"stop":4013.934,"duration":5.51},{"text":"I think the Commission would welcome, they are taking on this job.","start":4013.934,"stop":4018.634,"duration":4.7},{"text":"The Commission does not wish to monopolize the policing of this advertising but it is the Commission's feeling that the States have not in fact been regulated.","start":4018.634,"stop":4027.3,"duration":8.67}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All the States -- all I get from your observation on the State -- from the brief of the States, which I haven't look at, is that they joined issue with you.","start":4027.3,"stop":4036.433,"duration":9.13},{"text":"Not that they avoid the question but they joined issue with you, to where you say the mere fact of their statutes on the books is not -- is not regulation, and they say that it is.","start":4036.433,"stop":4049.074,"duration":12.64}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":4049.074,"stop":4049.617,"duration":0.54},{"text":"They interpret McCarran.","start":4049.617,"stop":4050.127,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that it is of square conflict of -- of what the McCarran Act means, does it?","start":4050.127,"stop":4056.095,"duration":5.97}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes.","start":4056.095,"stop":4056.573,"duration":0.48},{"text":"That I'm not --","start":4056.573,"stop":4058.036,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) --","start":4058.036,"stop":4058.106,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"-- quite saying that there is that conflict of views as to the meaning of the statute.","start":4058.106,"stop":4061.603,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They -- they -- occurs to me, they say that this very -- just as a matter of statute -- of construction by this Court to regulate in the Constitution means sometimes doing nothing.","start":4061.603,"stop":4075.066,"duration":13.46},{"text":"So, to regulate, means having passed the statute to do something.","start":4075.066,"stop":4078.324,"duration":3.26}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"That is so.","start":4078.324,"stop":4078.949,"duration":0.63},{"text":"They joined issue with us on that and my only point was that in their very full discussion of what they conceive to be all of the problems including the practical problems, they do no point to a single instance in which one of the States, and yet may (Voice Overlap) --","start":4078.949,"stop":4093.811,"duration":14.86}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Because they don't think that's your starting point.","start":4093.811,"stop":4096.015,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"They -- they deal with the problems of regulation.","start":4096.015,"stop":4098.595,"duration":2.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4098.595,"stop":4098.8,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"And my feeling, if I may say so in further answer to the question, is that probably the reasons that the States had not dealt with this is because of the proportions of -- that the problem has assumed especially in the light of the mail-order business.","start":4098.8,"stop":4116.462,"duration":17.66},{"text":"Nationally, it does business in 48 States.","start":4116.462,"stop":4119.167,"duration":2.7},{"text":"Most of these States -- most of these companies likewise are multi-State operations.","start":4119.167,"stop":4125.557,"duration":6.39},{"text":"If the States were attempt -- to attempt to deal with the practices of the 41 companies, respondents in the Federal Trade Commission's pending cases, they would have to bring over 1000 proceedings, assuming that that they could deal, which we seriously doubt, with many of the companies whose operations are mail-order operations.","start":4125.557,"stop":4142.756,"duration":17.2}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do I understand correctly?","start":4142.756,"stop":4144.089,"duration":1.33},{"text":"There's no mail-order situation before us?","start":4144.089,"stop":4146.542,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"You understand that correctly, Your Honor.","start":4146.542,"stop":4148.461,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"May I just ask a question about that?","start":4148.461,"stop":4149.444,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":4149.444,"stop":4151.973,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it your belief that to decide this case against them -- if it should be decided against them, in connection with the non-mail order houses, would necessarily decide that the same with the ways -- requires to decide the same way with reference to mail-order houses or do you draw a distinction?","start":4151.973,"stop":4173.434,"duration":21.46}]},{"speakerName":"Ralph S. Spritzer","textObjs":[{"text":"My answer would be that it would not necessary lead you to the same conclusion, Your Honor.","start":4173.434,"stop":4179.055,"duration":5.62}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Apr  9 - 10, 1958","petitioner":"Federal Trade Commission","respondent":"National Casualty Company","docket":"435","citation":"357 US 560 (1958)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/357/560","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 30, 1958"}